// MedMasters : Gynae & Obs Paper 2: Antenatal & Natal Care
// 280 MCQs
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['gynae_p2_antenatal'] = [
    {q:'A woman with a regular 28-day menstrual cycle reports her last menstrual period began on 10 March 2024. According to Naegele\'s rule, what is her estimated date of delivery (EDD)?',o:['10 December 2024','17 January 2025','3 December 2024','17 December 2024'],a:3,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule estimates the date of delivery by adding 7 days to the first day of the LMP, subtracting 3 months, and adding 1 year, assuming a regular 28-day cycle.<br><br>Applied to 10 March 2024: add 7 days gives 17 March, subtract 3 months gives 17 December 2023, add 1 year gives 17 December 2024. The rule assumes a 14-day follicular phase and a 280-day total gestation.<br><br>A (10 December 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. B (17 January 2025) adds an extra month. C (3 December 2024) subtracts rather than adds 7 days.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman presents for booking at 10 weeks gestation. Which investigation is routinely recommended at the first antenatal visit to screen for hemoglobinopathy?',o:['Peripheral blood smear','Serum ferritin level','Hemoglobin electrophoresis','Reticulocyte count'],a:2,
    e:`Hemoglobin electrophoresis at booking identifies thalassaemia trait and other haemoglobin variants in women from at-risk ethnic groups, allowing partner testing and prenatal counselling.<br><br>Carrier rates for alpha and beta thalassaemia are high in South Asian, Mediterranean, Middle Eastern and African populations. The Family Origin Questionnaire and FBC indices guide selection for confirmatory electrophoresis.<br><br>A (peripheral smear) suggests morphology only and misses thalassaemia trait. B (ferritin) reflects iron stores, not haemoglobin variants. D (reticulocyte count) measures erythropoietic activity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman\'s LMP was 5 June 2023 and she has regular 30-day cycles. What is the most appropriate method to accurately determine gestational age if the exact LMP is uncertain?',o:['First-trimester crown-rump length ultrasound','Second-trimester ultrasound biparietal diameter','Fundal height measurement','Abdominal circumference measurement'],a:0,
    e:`First-trimester crown-rump length ultrasound between 11+3 and 13+6 weeks is the most accurate method of dating, with CRL between 45 and 84 mm giving minimal biological variability in fetal size.<br><br>Beyond 14 weeks the head circumference is used. Beyond 20 weeks dating becomes progressively less accurate because genes and environment cause variation in fetal size, which is why late booking is suboptimal.<br><br>B (second-trimester BPD) is less accurate than first-trimester CRL. C (fundal height) is unreliable for dating. D (abdominal circumference) assesses growth, not gestational age.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'During antenatal booking, which infection screening is universally recommended in pregnancy to prevent vertical transmission and allow timely intervention?',o:['Rubella IgG antibody','HIV screening test','Cytomegalovirus IgM','Hepatitis A serology'],a:1,
    e:`HIV screening is universally offered at booking because antenatal interventions reduce vertical transmission from 25 to 30 percent down to less than 2 percent through antiretroviral therapy and delivery planning.<br><br>In the UK transmission rates have fallen to about 0.57 percent. Interventions include ART from 24 weeks, planned caesarean for high viral load, intrapartum AZT, and avoidance of breastfeeding where safe alternatives exist.<br><br>A (rubella IgG) is no longer routine in the UK since 2016. C (CMV IgM) is not part of routine booking screen. D (hepatitis A) is not routinely screened in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman reports LMP on 1 February 2024 with regular cycles. According to Naegele\'s rule, what is her EDD?',o:['15 December 2024','8 December 2024','1 November 2024','8 November 2024'],a:3,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 1 February 2024: add 7 days gives 8 February, subtract 3 months gives 8 November 2023, add 1 year gives 8 November 2024.<br><br>The rule assumes a regular 28-day cycle with ovulation on day 14 and a total gestation of 280 days from LMP. Cycle length variation requires correction by adding or subtracting days from the calculated EDD.<br><br>A (8 December 2024) adds an extra month. B (15 December 2024) compounds two errors. C (1 November 2024) ignores the 7-day addition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A 24-year-old primigravida presents at 8 weeks for antenatal booking. Which investigation is essential for identifying risk of hemolytic disease of the newborn?',o:['Direct Coombs test','Serum bilirubin','Blood group and Rh typing','Serum LDH'],a:2,
    e:`Blood group and Rhesus typing at booking identifies rhesus D-negative women, who require counselling on the risk of isoimmunisation by a rhesus D-positive fetus and antenatal anti-D prophylaxis at 28 weeks.<br><br>Rhesus isoimmunisation is the leading cause of haemolytic disease of the newborn. Antibody screening at 28 weeks also detects atypical antibodies. Postpartum anti-D is given when cord blood confirms a rhesus D-positive infant.<br><br>A (direct Coombs) detects antibody on neonatal red cells, not maternal risk. B (bilirubin) is a downstream marker. D (LDH) reflects haemolysis nonspecifically.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with irregular cycles is unsure of her LMP. At booking, ultrasound shows crown-rump length corresponding to 11 weeks 3 days. Which approach is recommended for calculating EDD?',o:['Use LMP estimate despite discrepancy','Use CRL-based dating as definitive gestational age','Average LMP and ultrasound dating','Repeat ultrasound at 20 weeks'],a:1,
    e:`When the LMP is uncertain or cycles are irregular, first-trimester CRL between 11+3 and 13+6 weeks is taken as the definitive gestational age because biological variation in fetal size at this stage is minimal.<br><br>A CRL of 45 to 84 mm is the optimal range for dating. Reliable dating prevents misdiagnosis of growth restriction and inappropriate induction for postdates pregnancy. CRL is preferred over LMP when the two disagree.<br><br>A (LMP despite discrepancy) is unreliable when cycles are irregular. C (averaging) gives an inferior estimate. D (repeat at 20 weeks) is less accurate than first-trimester dating.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening is recommended at booking to detect maternal infection that may cause congenital deafness and cataracts if acquired in early pregnancy?',o:['Rubella IgG antibody test','Parvovirus B19 serology','Toxoplasma IgM test','HSV PCR'],a:0,
    e:`Rubella IgG at booking confirms maternal immunity. Primary rubella infection in early pregnancy can cause congenital rubella syndrome, with cataracts, sensorineural deafness, cardiac defects and intellectual disability.<br><br>Although the UK stopped routine rubella screening in 2016 because the disease is now eliminated, IgG testing remains relevant in lower-immunity populations. Non-immune women are offered MMR vaccination after delivery.<br><br>B (parvovirus B19) causes fetal anaemia and hydrops, not cataracts. C (toxoplasma IgM) marks acute infection. D (HSV PCR) is not a routine booking test.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with a 28-day cycle has LMP on 20 September 2023. What is the estimated date of delivery?',o:['20 June 2024','27 June 2024','20 May 2024','27 May 2024'],a:1,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 20 September 2023: add 7 days gives 27 September, subtract 3 months gives 27 June 2023, add 1 year gives 27 June 2024.<br><br>The 280-day rule applies to a regular 28-day cycle with ovulation around day 14. Where the cycle differs from 28 days, an adjustment of plus or minus the difference is added to the calculated date.<br><br>A (20 June 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. C (20 May 2024) ignores both 7 days and shifts the month wrongly. D (27 May 2024) shifts the month back by one.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A 26-year-old woman presents for antenatal booking. Which infection screening is routinely recommended to prevent congenital syphilis?',o:['Dark field microscopy','TPHA only','VDRL or RPR test','Treponemal IgM antibody'],a:2,
    e:`VDRL or RPR is the routine non-treponemal screening test for syphilis at booking. Untreated maternal syphilis can cause miscarriage, stillbirth or active congenital infection in the newborn, and treatment with penicillin in pregnancy is safe and effective.<br><br>Reactive non-treponemal tests are confirmed with a treponemal test such as TPHA or FTA-abs. UK incidence has risen, and screening continues despite low absolute numbers because the public health benefit is large.<br><br>A (dark field microscopy) requires an active lesion. B (TPHA only) is confirmatory, not for screening. D (treponemal IgM) is rarely used as a primary screen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient reports LMP on 12 August 2023 with regular cycles. What is the estimated date of delivery using Naegele\'s rule?',o:['5 May 2024','12 May 2024','26 May 2024','19 May 2024'],a:3,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 12 August 2023: add 7 days gives 19 August, subtract 3 months gives 19 May 2023, add 1 year gives 19 May 2024.<br><br>The estimated date assumes ovulation on day 14 of a regular 28-day cycle and a total gestation of 280 days. Only 5 percent of women deliver on the calculated date itself; most deliver within a 2-week window around it.<br><br>A (5 May 2024) shifts the day wrongly. B (12 May 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. C (26 May 2024) adds 14 days instead of 7.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening during antenatal booking is specifically recommended for identifying carriers who may transmit infection to the fetus through placental crossing and cause severe fetal anemia?',o:['Parvovirus B19 IgM','Toxoplasmosis screening','CMV IgG','HSV culture'],a:0,
    e:`Parvovirus B19 IgM identifies recent maternal infection. Vertical transmission in the first half of pregnancy can cause severe fetal anaemia, hydrops fetalis and intrauterine death due to viral suppression of fetal erythropoiesis.<br><br>Risk of fetal hydrops is greatest with infection between 9 and 20 weeks. Suspected exposure is investigated with maternal IgG and IgM, and infected pregnancies are followed by serial ultrasound to detect fetal anaemia.<br><br>B (toxoplasmosis) causes intracranial calcification and chorioretinitis, not isolated fetal anaemia. C (CMV IgG) reflects past exposure. D (HSV culture) detects active genital lesions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with regular cycles reports LMP on 5 April 2024. Using Naegele\'s rule, what is her EDD?',o:['12 December 2024','5 January 2025','5 December 2024','12 January 2025'],a:3,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 5 April 2024: add 7 days gives 12 April, subtract 3 months gives 12 January 2024, add 1 year gives 12 January 2025.<br><br>The rule assumes a regular 28-day cycle and is most accurate in the first trimester. When the LMP gives a date discrepant with first-trimester CRL by more than 7 days, ultrasound dating is used instead.<br><br>A (12 December 2024) shifts the month back by one. B (5 January 2025) ignores the 7-day addition. C (5 December 2024) compounds two errors.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'At booking, screening for hepatitis B infection is recommended primarily to reduce which risk?',o:['Maternal hepatic failure','Preterm labor','Neonatal vertical transmission','Placental abruption'],a:2,
    e:`Hepatitis B screening at booking allows postnatal vaccine and immunoglobulin administration to the neonate, which is approximately 95 percent effective in preventing vertical transmission and chronic infant infection.<br><br>Without intervention, around 90 percent of babies born to HBsAg-positive mothers develop chronic infection, which carries lifelong risk of cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma. The infant receives vaccine at birth, 1 month and 6 months.<br><br>A (maternal hepatic failure) is not the screening goal. B (preterm labour) is not directly linked to HBV. D (placental abruption) is unrelated to hepatitis B status.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman attends booking at 9 weeks. Which test helps identify women at risk for rhesus isoimmunization requiring anti-D prophylaxis?',o:['Direct Coombs test','Antibody screen (indirect Coombs test)','Hemoglobin electrophoresis','Serum ferritin'],a:1,
    e:`The indirect antiglobulin test, also called indirect Coombs or antibody screen, detects atypical maternal red cell antibodies including anti-D and identifies pregnancies at risk of haemolytic disease requiring monitoring or anti-D prophylaxis.<br><br>Rhesus D-negative women receive routine antenatal anti-D at 28 weeks (or at 28 and 34 weeks) and additional anti-D after potentially sensitising events such as bleeding, amniocentesis or trauma.<br><br>A (direct Coombs) tests neonatal red cells for bound antibody. C (electrophoresis) screens for haemoglobinopathy. D (ferritin) measures iron stores.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with uncertain LMP and irregular cycles. Ultrasound at 19 weeks shows fetal measurements corresponding to 17 weeks. Which gestational age should be used for EDD calculation?',o:['Ultrasound dating','LMP-based age','Fundal height measurement','Quickening history'],a:0,
    e:`When LMP is uncertain or cycles are irregular and ultrasound dating differs from menstrual dating by more than the accepted threshold, ultrasound dating takes precedence as the more reliable estimate.<br><br>First-trimester CRL has the smallest biological variability and is preferred. Beyond 14 weeks head circumference is used. Beyond 20 weeks variability rises and ultrasound dating is less reliable.<br><br>B (LMP-based) is unreliable here given irregular cycles. C (fundal height) is not a dating method. D (quickening) is felt at variable gestations and is unreliable for dating.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening is performed during antenatal booking to identify immunity status and prevent congenital rubella syndrome?',o:['Rubella IgM antibody','Rubella IgG antibody','Viral culture','PCR for rubella'],a:1,
    e:`Rubella IgG identifies women who are immune. Non-immune women are advised to avoid contact with infected individuals and offered MMR vaccination after delivery to protect future pregnancies from congenital rubella syndrome.<br><br>Over 90 percent of UK children receive MMR by age 2, and rubella infection in pregnancy is now very rare. The vaccine is contraindicated in pregnancy because it contains live attenuated virus.<br><br>A (rubella IgM) marks acute infection, not immunity. C (viral culture) is impractical for screening. D (PCR) is used only for confirming acute fetal infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman reports LMP on 15 November 2023. What is her estimated date of delivery?',o:['15 September 2024','15 August 2024','22 September 2024','22 August 2024'],a:3,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 15 November 2023: add 7 days gives 22 November, subtract 3 months gives 22 August 2023, add 1 year gives 22 August 2024.<br><br>The expected date of delivery is calculated from the first day of the last menstrual period, not the date of conception. The rule is reliable only when the cycle is regular and the LMP is certain.<br><br>A (15 September 2024) ignores the 7-day addition and shifts the month. B (15 August 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. C (22 September 2024) shifts the month forward.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old primigravida attends antenatal booking. Which screening is recommended to detect asymptomatic bacteriuria associated with pyelonephritis and preterm birth?',o:['Urine culture','Urine dipstick only','Serum creatinine','Urine microscopy only'],a:0,
    e:`A mid-stream urine sample is sent for culture and sensitivity at booking to detect asymptomatic bacteriuria, which if untreated raises the risk of pyelonephritis and preterm delivery.<br><br>Routine urinalysis at every antenatal visit additionally tests for protein (renal disease, pre-eclampsia), persistent glycosuria (diabetes) and nitrites (urinary tract infection). Positive culture is treated with appropriate antibiotics.<br><br>B (dipstick alone) misses many asymptomatic infections. C (serum creatinine) measures renal function, not infection. D (microscopy alone) is less sensitive than culture for low-count bacteriuria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which booking investigation is essential to detect anemia that may affect maternal and fetal outcomes during pregnancy?',o:['Vitamin B12 level','Serum ferritin','Hemoglobin estimation','Reticulocyte count'],a:2,
    e:`Haemoglobin estimation as part of the booking full blood count detects anaemia, defined as Hb less than 110 g/l in the first trimester, and allows early treatment to optimise maternal and fetal outcomes.<br><br>The mean cell volume guides further investigation: microcytic anaemia suggests iron deficiency, while macrocytic anaemia suggests folate or B12 deficiency. A trial of oral iron is the usual first-line treatment.<br><br>A (B12) is a second-line investigation. B (ferritin) confirms iron deficiency once anaemia is identified. D (reticulocyte count) reflects bone marrow response, not anaemia presence.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with LMP on 1 July 2023 has regular cycles. What is the estimated date of delivery?',o:['8 May 2024','8 April 2024','1 April 2024','15 April 2024'],a:1,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 1 July 2023: add 7 days gives 8 July, subtract 3 months gives 8 April 2023, add 1 year gives 8 April 2024.<br><br>The rule remains the standard initial estimate of delivery date despite limitations. It is used to plan antenatal visits, screening windows, and timing of interventions such as antenatal anti-D prophylaxis at 28 weeks.<br><br>A (8 May 2024) shifts the month forward by one. C (1 April 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. D (15 April 2024) adds 14 days instead of 7.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'During antenatal booking, screening for which infection is recommended because untreated maternal infection can cause congenital cataracts, cardiac defects, and deafness?',o:['Rubella','Toxoplasmosis','Cytomegalovirus','Parvovirus B19'],a:0,
    e:`Rubella infection in early pregnancy can cause congenital rubella syndrome, comprising sensorineural deafness, cataracts, congenital heart defects (especially patent ductus arteriosus and pulmonary stenosis) and intellectual disability.<br><br>Risk of fetal damage is highest before 16 weeks. Maternal immunity is checked with rubella IgG; non-immune women receive MMR vaccine postnatally because the live attenuated vaccine is contraindicated during pregnancy.<br><br>B (toxoplasmosis) causes hydrocephalus, chorioretinitis and intracranial calcification. C (CMV) causes sensorineural deafness and microcephaly but not classic cataracts. D (parvovirus B19) causes fetal anaemia and hydrops.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with LMP on 10 October 2023 attends clinic. What is the estimated date of delivery?',o:['10 July 2024','3 July 2024','17 July 2024','24 July 2024'],a:2,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 10 October 2023: add 7 days gives 17 October, subtract 3 months gives 17 July 2023, add 1 year gives 17 July 2024.<br><br>The rule is a derivative of a 280-day gestation calculated from the LMP. For cycle lengths longer or shorter than 28 days the difference is added to or subtracted from the calculated date to refine the estimate.<br><br>A (10 July 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. B (3 July 2024) subtracts 7 days instead of adding. D (24 July 2024) adds 14 days.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening during pregnancy allows prevention of neonatal HIV infection through antiretroviral therapy and delivery planning?',o:['CD4 count','Western blot only','PCR viral load','HIV ELISA test'],a:3,
    e:`HIV antibody (ELISA) testing is the routine booking screen, allowing identification of infected women so that antiretroviral therapy and delivery planning can reduce vertical transmission to less than 2 percent.<br><br>ART is started by 24 weeks if treatment-naive. Planned caesarean is offered if viral load is at least 400 copies/ml at 36 weeks. Where safe alternatives exist, breastfeeding is avoided. Repeat screening at 28 weeks is offered to those at ongoing risk.<br><br>A (CD4 count) measures immune status, not screening. B (Western blot only) is confirmatory, not primary. C (PCR viral load) is used to monitor known infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient reports LMP on 25 December 2023. What is the estimated date of delivery?',o:['25 September 2024','18 September 2024','1 October 2024','2 October 2024'],a:2,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 25 December 2023: add 7 days gives 1 January 2024, subtract 3 months gives 1 October 2023, add 1 year gives 1 October 2024.<br><br>When the 7-day addition crosses a month boundary, the day-and-month subtraction must be performed on the new date, not the original. The total gestation calculated remains 280 days from the LMP.<br><br>A (25 September 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. B (18 September 2024) subtracts 7 days. D (2 October 2024) shifts the day by one.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening during booking aims to prevent congenital syphilis by enabling early treatment with penicillin?',o:['VDRL test','TPHA screening','Dark field microscopy','Syphilis PCR'],a:0,
    e:`Non-treponemal serology, typically VDRL or RPR, is the booking screen for syphilis. Detection allows early treatment with parenteral penicillin, which is safe in pregnancy and effective in preventing congenital syphilis.<br><br>A reactive non-treponemal test is confirmed with a treponemal test such as TPHA. Untreated maternal syphilis carries a high risk of stillbirth, congenital infection or neonatal death. Treatment must be completed at least 30 days before delivery.<br><br>B (TPHA) is a confirmatory test, not the primary screen. C (dark field microscopy) requires an active lesion. D (syphilis PCR) is not a standard screening test.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with LMP on 3 March 2024 presents for antenatal care. What is her estimated date of delivery?',o:['3 December 2024','10 December 2024','17 December 2024','24 December 2024'],a:1,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 3 March 2024: add 7 days gives 10 March, subtract 3 months gives 10 December 2023, add 1 year gives 10 December 2024.<br><br>The total gestation is calculated as 280 days from the first day of the LMP, equivalent to 40 weeks. The rule remains the simplest first estimate, with first-trimester ultrasound used to confirm or replace it.<br><br>A (3 December 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. C (17 December 2024) adds 14 days. D (24 December 2024) adds 21 days.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infection screening during pregnancy is performed primarily to detect latent infection that may cause congenital anomalies if primary infection occurs during pregnancy?',o:['Epstein-Barr virus serology','Hepatitis C antibody','HSV culture','Toxoplasma IgG and IgM'],a:3,
    e:`Toxoplasma IgG and IgM identify maternal immunity status and acute infection. Primary maternal infection in pregnancy can cross the placenta and cause hydrocephalus, intracranial calcification, chorioretinitis and intellectual disability.<br><br>Risk of vertical transmission rises with gestation but severity falls; first-trimester transmission is least frequent but most severe. Avoidance of undercooked meat, cat litter and unwashed produce is the main preventive advice.<br><br>A (EBV serology) is not part of routine screening. B (hepatitis C antibody) is offered only to high-risk women. C (HSV culture) detects active genital lesions, not latent infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with LMP on 8 January 2024 has regular cycles. What is the estimated date of delivery?',o:['8 October 2024','15 October 2024','1 October 2024','22 October 2024'],a:1,
    e:`Naegele\'s rule applied to LMP 8 January 2024: add 7 days gives 15 January, subtract 3 months gives 15 October 2023, add 1 year gives 15 October 2024.<br><br>The rule provides a quick clinical estimate. First-trimester CRL between 11+3 and 13+6 weeks is more accurate and is used to confirm or replace the menstrual estimate when there is a discrepancy of more than 7 days.<br><br>A (8 October 2024) ignores the 7-day addition. C (1 October 2024) subtracts 7 days. D (22 October 2024) adds 14 days.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A 25-year-old primigravida attends antenatal booking. Which infection screening is recommended to detect hepatitis infection associated with risk of neonatal chronic liver disease?',o:['Hepatitis A IgM','Hepatitis E IgM','Hepatitis D antibody','Hepatitis B surface antigen'],a:3,
    e:`Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) is the booking screen for hepatitis B. Detection of HBsAg in maternal blood indicates active infection and identifies pregnancies at risk of vertical transmission and chronic infant infection.<br><br>Without intervention, around 90 percent of babies born to HBsAg-positive mothers develop chronic infection, with high lifetime risk of cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma. Combined immunoglobulin and vaccine at birth prevents about 95 percent of transmission.<br><br>A (hepatitis A IgM) screens acute hepatitis A, which is rarely vertically transmitted. B (hepatitis E) is not a routine screen. C (hepatitis D antibody) is relevant only as co-infection with HBV.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'During the first stage of labour, the primary physiological process responsible for cervical effacement is:',o:['Descent of the fetal head','Dilatation of the lower uterine segment','Retraction of uterine muscle fibers','Rupture of the membranes'],a:2,
    e:`Effacement is the shortening and thinning of the cervix as it is progressively incorporated into the lower uterine segment. The driving force is retraction of upper segment myometrial fibres pulling on the cervix.<br><br>Retraction occurs because each contraction does not return the muscle fibres to their original length. The thicker upper segment shortens while the lower segment and cervix become thinner and stretched.<br><br>A (descent of fetal head) helps dilatation more than effacement. B (lower segment dilatation) is a passive consequence, not the cause. D (membrane rupture) is independent of effacement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The first stage of labour ends when:',o:['Cervix is fully dilated','Cervix is dilated to 8 cm','Cervix is fully effaced','Membranes rupture'],a:0,
    e:`The first stage ends when the cervix is fully dilated to 10 cm. It begins with the diagnosis of labour, regular painful contractions producing cervical change, and is divided into latent and active phases.<br><br>The latent phase covers the time from labour onset to 3 to 4 cm dilatation; the active phase runs from 4 cm to full dilatation. Average primigravid first stage is around 8 hours and rarely exceeds 18 hours.<br><br>B (8 cm) is mid active phase, not the end. C (full effacement) usually occurs by 4 cm. D (membrane rupture) does not define stage transition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida in active labour shows progressive cervical dilatation. The most important physiological force responsible for cervical dilatation is:',o:['Maternal bearing down efforts','Fetal movements','Pelvic ligament relaxation','Uterine contractions'],a:3,
    e:`Cervical dilatation is driven by coordinated uterine contractions of the upper segment, which generate a directional force transmitted via the lower segment and the presenting part to the cervix.<br><br>Each contraction increases intrauterine pressure to 30 to 60 mmHg, retracts upper segment fibres, and pulls the cervix open. Maternal pushing in the second stage adds expulsive force after full dilatation, not before.<br><br>A (maternal pushing) is the second stage contributor, not first stage. B (fetal movements) play no significant role in dilatation. C (pelvic ligament relaxation) increases pelvic capacity but does not dilate the cervix.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In the first stage of labour, uterine contractions originate from:',o:['Lower uterine segment','Cervical ring','Fundal pacemaker area','Broad ligament'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine contractions originate from a functional pacemaker area near the fundus and cornua, where myometrial cells have the highest spontaneous activity. The wave then spreads downward through gap junctions.<br><br>Although a single histological pacemaker has not been demonstrated, fundal dominance is consistently observed. Gap junctions, formed at term under prostaglandin influence, allow electrical coordination across the myometrium.<br><br>A (lower segment) is mainly passive in labour. B (cervical ring) is not the source of contractions. D (broad ligament) contains no contractile myometrium.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During normal labour, uterine contractions show a pattern known as polarity. This means:',o:['Upper segment contracts and retracts while lower segment relaxes','Cervix contracts while fundus relaxes','Entire uterus contracts simultaneously','Cervix dilates independently of uterine contractions'],a:0,
    e:`Polarity describes the coordinated reciprocal action of the uterus during labour: the upper segment contracts and retracts strongly while the lower segment and cervix relax, soften and stretch.<br><br>This pattern produces a directional expulsive force. Loss of polarity, such as a contracting cervix or a non-retracting upper segment, results in dysfunctional labour and arrest of progress.<br><br>B (cervix contracts, fundus relaxes) reverses normal polarity. C (whole uterus simultaneously) describes uncoordinated activity. D (cervix dilates independently) is not a physiological pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In the first stage of labour, effacement usually occurs before dilatation in:',o:['Multiparous women','Primigravida','Grand multipara','Women with polyhydramnios'],a:1,
    e:`In primigravidae, effacement is usually complete before significant dilatation begins. In multiparous women effacement and dilatation typically occur simultaneously because the cervix is already partly effaced.<br><br>This anatomical difference shortens the latent phase in multiparous women. By 36 weeks the cervix is approximately 3 cm long; in early labour the multiparous cervix is often already shortened.<br><br>A (multiparous) shows simultaneous effacement and dilatation. C (grand multipara) labours rapidly. D (polyhydramnios) does not change the order of effacement and dilatation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The average duration of the first stage of labour in a primigravida is approximately:',o:['4 hours','6 hours','12 hours','18 hours'],a:2,
    e:`The average first stage in a primigravida is around 8 hours and rarely exceeds 18 hours. A duration of 12 hours fits within normal limits and reflects typical primigravid latent and active phase durations combined.<br><br>Latent phase usually lasts 3 to 8 hours; active phase 2 to 6 hours. Cervical dilatation in active phase normally proceeds at 1 cm or more per hour and is considered abnormal if less than 1 cm in 2 hours.<br><br>A (4 hours) is too short for primigravid first stage. B (6 hours) is shorter than typical. D (18 hours) is the upper limit of normal, not the average.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most important hormone responsible for initiation of uterine contractions during labour is:',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin from the maternal posterior pituitary is the principal hormone driving uterine contractions during labour. Its action is amplified by the Ferguson reflex, in which cervical and vaginal stretch increases pituitary release.<br><br>Oxytocin raises intracellular calcium in myometrial cells via receptor coupling. Receptor density in the myometrium rises markedly near term, increasing sensitivity. Synthetic oxytocin is used clinically to augment labour.<br><br>A (progesterone) maintains uterine relaxation and is functionally withdrawn before labour. C (estrogen) opposes progesterone but does not directly drive contractions. D (prolactin) acts on the breast.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The second stage of labour begins with:',o:['Full cervical dilatation','Rupture of membranes','Engagement of fetal head','Onset of uterine contractions'],a:0,
    e:`The second stage begins at full cervical dilatation (10 cm) and ends with delivery of the baby. It is subdivided into a passive phase, before involuntary expulsive contractions, and an active phase with maternal pushing.<br><br>Active second stage should normally last no more than 2 hours in a nulliparous woman and 1 hour in a multiparous woman. Beyond 3 hours, maternal and fetal morbidity rises and operative delivery is often required.<br><br>B (membrane rupture) does not define stage onset. C (engagement) usually occurs in late pregnancy or first stage. D (onset of contractions) marks the start of first stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The major force responsible for expulsion of the fetus during the second stage of labour is:',o:['Cervical dilatation','Fetal movements','Placental separation','Maternal bearing down efforts'],a:3,
    e:`Maternal bearing-down efforts during the active second stage provide the major expulsive force, supplementing uterine contractions. The Valsalva manoeuvre raises intra-abdominal pressure and drives fetal descent.<br><br>Bearing down is reflexly triggered when the fetal head stretches the pelvic floor and vagina (Ferguson reflex). Epidural analgesia can blunt this reflex, prolonging the passive phase and altering second-stage management.<br><br>A (cervical dilatation) is complete before second stage begins. B (fetal movements) do not provide expulsive force. C (placental separation) occurs in third stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The typical duration of the second stage of labour in a primigravida without epidural analgesia is:',o:['Up to 2 hours','30 minutes','10-20 minutes','4 hours'],a:0,
    e:`In a primigravida without epidural, the active second stage should last no more than 2 hours. Beyond this, both maternal and fetal morbidity rise and assisted delivery is often considered.<br><br>With epidural anaesthesia a passive second stage of 1 to 2 hours is recommended to allow descent and rotation before active pushing. The total time to delivery should not exceed 4 hours from full dilatation.<br><br>B (30 minutes) is shorter than typical. C (10 to 20 minutes) is unusually fast. D (4 hours) is the upper limit including epidural use, not the typical primigravid duration.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The Ferguson reflex during labour refers to:',o:['Maternal tachycardia during contractions','Reflex inhibition of uterine contractions','Reflex increase in oxytocin secretion due to cervical stretching','Reflex fetal heart acceleration'],a:2,
    e:`The Ferguson reflex is a neuroendocrine reflex in which pressure from the fetal presenting part stretches the cervix and upper vagina, triggering increased oxytocin release from the maternal posterior pituitary.<br><br>The reflex amplifies labour as it progresses, generating a positive feedback loop: more oxytocin produces stronger contractions, greater cervical stretch, and further oxytocin release. It also contributes to the bearing-down urge.<br><br>A (maternal tachycardia) is not a neuroendocrine reflex. B (inhibition of contractions) is the opposite of the actual response. D (fetal heart acceleration) is unrelated to the Ferguson reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the second stage of labour, the cardinal movement that follows engagement is:',o:['Extension','Internal rotation','Descent','Flexion'],a:3,
    e:`After engagement, the next cardinal movement is flexion of the fetal head. Flexion is a passive movement caused by the fetal head meeting the resistance of the pelvic walls and pelvic floor.<br><br>Flexion brings the chin onto the chest and presents the suboccipito-bregmatic diameter (9.5 cm), the smallest longitudinal diameter, to the maternal pelvis. A poorly flexed head presents larger diameters and prolongs labour.<br><br>A (extension) occurs at delivery of the head, not after engagement. B (internal rotation) follows flexion. C (descent) is continuous and overlaps multiple movements.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological mechanism that prevents uterine muscle fibers from returning to their original length after contraction is called:',o:['Relaxation','Retraction','Effacement','Involution'],a:1,
    e:`Retraction is the property of uterine smooth muscle that prevents myocytes from returning to their original length after contraction. The actin-myosin interaction occurs along the full filament length, leaving fibres progressively shortened.<br><br>Retraction develops the thicker actively contracting upper segment, while the lower segment becomes thinner and more stretched. After delivery, sustained retraction compresses myometrial blood vessels and prevents postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (relaxation) returns muscle to resting length, the opposite property. C (effacement) is shortening of the cervix. D (involution) is the postpartum return of the uterus to non-pregnant size.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The third stage of labour begins with:',o:['Delivery of the fetal head','Full cervical dilatation','Onset of uterine contractions','Delivery of the baby'],a:3,
    e:`The third stage of labour begins immediately after delivery of the baby and ends with complete delivery of the placenta and membranes. It usually takes 5 to 10 minutes with active management.<br><br>Placental separation occurs because the uterus reduces in volume after fetal expulsion, and continued retraction of the lattice-like myometrial fibres creates a cleavage plane in the decidua basalis.<br><br>A (delivery of head) is part of second stage. B (full dilatation) ends first stage. C (onset of contractions) marks start of first stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common mechanism of placental separation during the third stage of labour is:',o:['Schultze mechanism','Matthews Duncan mechanism','Couvelaire mechanism','Bandl mechanism'],a:0,
    e:`The Schultze mechanism is the most common pattern of placental separation, occurring in roughly 80 percent of deliveries. The placenta separates from its centre first and is delivered fetal surface outward.<br><br>Retroplacental blood is contained behind the placenta as it descends, so external bleeding is delayed until after expulsion. The alternative Matthews Duncan pattern separates from the margin with earlier external bleeding.<br><br>B (Matthews Duncan) is the less common edge-first mechanism. C (Couvelaire) is uterine apoplexy seen in severe abruption. D (Bandl) refers to a pathological retraction ring.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In the Schultze mechanism of placental separation, the placenta separates:',o:['From the margin first','From the center first','Simultaneously from all sides','From the lower uterine segment'],a:1,
    e:`In the Schultze mechanism, the placenta separates beginning at its centre. A retroplacental haematoma forms behind the central area and progressively peels the placenta from the decidua basalis outwards.<br><br>Because separation begins centrally and the margins detach last, blood is concealed behind the placenta and external bleeding is minimal until after expulsion. The placenta presents fetal (shiny) surface first at the introitus.<br><br>A (margin first) describes Matthews Duncan, not Schultze. C (simultaneous) is not a recognised mechanism. D (lower segment) is anatomical, not a separation pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'One of the earliest clinical signs of placental separation is:',o:['Uterine contraction pain','Cervical dilatation','Lengthening of the umbilical cord','Fetal head descent'],a:2,
    e:`Apparent lengthening of the umbilical cord at the introitus is one of the earliest and most reliable signs of placental separation. As the placenta descends into the lower segment, the cord visible externally lengthens.<br><br>Other signs include a small gush of blood from the placental bed, rising of the uterine fundus to above the umbilicus, and a firm globular feel of the contracted uterus on palpation.<br><br>A (uterine contraction pain) is non-specific. B (cervical dilatation) belongs to first stage. D (fetal head descent) belongs to second stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the third stage of labour, the uterus becomes:',o:['Firm and globular','Soft and enlarged','Flaccid and elongated','Displaced laterally'],a:0,
    e:`Following placental separation the uterus contracts firmly and assumes a globular shape, with the fundus rising above the umbilicus. Palpation of a firm globular fundus is a classic sign of separation.<br><br>The shape change occurs because the placenta no longer fills the uterine cavity, and the upper segment is now contracted and retracted. A boggy uterus, by contrast, suggests atony and impending haemorrhage.<br><br>B (soft and enlarged) suggests uterine atony, not normal third stage. C (flaccid and elongated) is not the normal finding. D (lateral displacement) suggests a full bladder, not separation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Controlled cord traction during active management of the third stage of labour is performed primarily to:',o:['Increase uterine contractions','Prevent fetal distress','Shorten second stage of labour','Prevent postpartum hemorrhage'],a:3,
    e:`Controlled cord traction, given as part of active management, expedites delivery of the separated placenta and reduces the incidence of postpartum haemorrhage from around 15 percent to 5 percent.<br><br>Active management combines intramuscular oxytocin (10 IU) at delivery of the anterior shoulder, early cord clamping (or delayed for 1 to 3 minutes for autotransfusion), and controlled cord traction with the suprapubic hand guarding the uterus.<br><br>A (increase contractions) is the role of oxytocin, not traction. B (prevent fetal distress) is irrelevant after delivery. C (shorten second stage) is unrelated to third stage management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological cause of placental separation during the third stage is mainly:',o:['Cervical dilatation','Fetal movements','Uterine contraction and retraction','Maternal pushing'],a:2,
    e:`Placental separation results from the reduction in uterine volume after fetal expulsion, combined with continued contraction and retraction of the lattice-arranged myometrial fibres, which creates a cleavage plane in the decidua basalis.<br><br>The placenta itself does not contract, so as the underlying myometrium shortens the placental implantation area decreases and the placenta sheers off the uterine wall and lies free in the lower segment.<br><br>A (cervical dilatation) is irrelevant to separation. B (fetal movements) cease after delivery. D (maternal pushing) may aid expulsion but does not cause separation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most reliable clinical sign of placental separation is:',o:['Uterine fundus becomes firm and globular','Lengthening of umbilical cord','Sudden gush of blood','Maternal urge to push'],a:1,
    e:`Apparent lengthening of the umbilical cord at the vulva is the most reliable single sign of placental separation. It indicates that the placenta has detached from the uterine wall and descended into the lower segment.<br><br>Other supportive signs include a small gush of blood, the uterus becoming firm and globular, and the fundus rising above the umbilicus. Together these are checked before controlled cord traction is applied.<br><br>A (firm globular fundus) is supportive but less specific. C (gush of blood) may also occur with partial separation. D (urge to push) belongs to second stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In multiparous women, the second stage of labour usually lasts:',o:['Up to 1 hour','5-10 minutes','Up to 3 hours','Up to 5 hours'],a:0,
    e:`In multiparous women the active second stage should last no more than 1 hour. Greater perineal compliance, an already-stretched birth canal, and more efficient maternal effort produce shorter second stages than in primigravidae.<br><br>Beyond 1 hour in a multipara, the diagnosis of arrest must be considered, with attention to malposition, malpresentation or cephalopelvic disproportion. Oxytocin augmentation is used cautiously due to higher rupture risk.<br><br>B (5 to 10 minutes) is unusually rapid. C (3 hours) exceeds the upper limit. D (5 hours) is far beyond normal limits.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological process that shortens the cervix during labour is called:',o:['Dilatation','Engagement','Retraction','Effacement'],a:3,
    e:`Effacement is the process by which the cervix shortens in length as it is taken up into the lower uterine segment. It is usually expressed as a percentage of the original cervical length.<br><br>By 36 weeks the cervix is approximately 3 cm long. In a primigravid it effaces fully (becomes flush with the lower segment) before significant dilatation; in a multipara, effacement and dilatation overlap.<br><br>A (dilatation) is opening of the os in centimetres, not shortening. B (engagement) is descent of the presenting part. C (retraction) is permanent shortening of myometrial fibres.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The hormone responsible for cervical ripening prior to labour is primarily:',o:['Oxytocin','Prostaglandins','Relaxin','Estrogen'],a:1,
    e:`Prostaglandins, particularly PGE2 and PGF2-alpha, are the principal mediators of cervical ripening. They increase proteolytic activity, reduce collagen and elastin, and replace dermatan sulphate with hydrophilic hyaluronic acid.<br><br>These changes raise water content and soften the cervix. Prostaglandins also increase gap junction formation between myometrial cells, coordinating contractions. Synthetic PGE2 (dinoprostone) is used clinically for induction.<br><br>A (oxytocin) drives contractions but does not ripen the cervix. C (relaxin) softens pelvic ligaments and contributes minimally to cervical change. D (estrogen) opposes progesterone but is not the primary ripener.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the upper uterine segment becomes progressively thicker due to:',o:['Dilatation','Effacement','Retraction','Stretching'],a:2,
    e:`Retraction is the progressive permanent shortening of upper segment myometrial fibres after each contraction. With successive contractions, fibres shorten further, producing a thicker, actively contracting upper segment.<br><br>The result is functional polarity: the upper segment thickens and shortens while the lower segment becomes thinner and stretched, generating the directional force that opens the cervix.<br><br>A (dilatation) refers to the cervix opening. B (effacement) is shortening of the cervix. D (stretching) describes what happens to the lower segment, not the upper.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The ring formed between the upper and lower uterine segments during obstructed labour is known as:',o:['Schroeder ring','Hegar\'s ring','Ferguson ring','Bandl\'s ring'],a:3,
    e:`Bandl\'s ring is a pathological retraction ring that develops at the junction of the thick upper segment and the thinned-out lower segment in obstructed labour. It is visible or palpable as a transverse ridge on the abdomen.<br><br>The ring rises progressively as obstruction continues, and uterine rupture may occur if labour is not promptly relieved by caesarean section. It is most often seen in neglected obstructed labour with cephalopelvic disproportion.<br><br>A (Schroeder ring) is not a recognised pathological retraction ring. B (Hegar\'s sign) is early-pregnancy softening of the lower segment. C (Ferguson) is a reflex, not a ring.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary force responsible for fetal descent during the second stage is:',o:['Amniotic fluid pressure','Placental pressure','Maternal bearing down efforts','Umbilical cord traction'],a:2,
    e:`During the active second stage, fetal descent is driven primarily by maternal bearing-down efforts (the Valsalva manoeuvre), supplementing the continuing force of uterine contractions of the upper segment.<br><br>Maternal pushing raises intra-abdominal pressure and adds expulsive force. Without effective pushing the descent stalls, especially when an epidural reduces the urge. The pelvic floor guides the head into anterior rotation as it descends.<br><br>A (amniotic fluid pressure) plays no role after rupture of membranes. B (placental pressure) does not generate descent. D (cord traction) is for placental delivery, not fetal descent.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the third stage of labour, average duration in normal delivery is:',o:['30 minutes','5 minutes','60 minutes','2 hours'],a:0,
    e:`A third stage lasting more than 30 minutes is defined as abnormal under standard active management; the placenta is then considered retained and may require manual removal under anaesthesia.<br><br>With active management the placenta is normally delivered within 5 to 10 minutes of the baby. With physiological management the threshold for retention is extended to 60 minutes, provided bleeding remains acceptable.<br><br>B (5 minutes) is the typical time, not the upper limit. C (60 minutes) applies only to physiological management. D (2 hours) is far beyond all definitions of normal third stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most important physiological mechanism preventing postpartum hemorrhage after placental delivery is:',o:['Cervical contraction','Retraction of uterine muscle fibers compressing blood vessels','Placental clot formation','Vaginal contraction'],a:1,
    e:`After placental delivery, retraction of the lattice-arranged myometrial fibres compresses the spiral arteries running through them, occluding bleeding from the placental bed. This mechanism is sometimes called living ligatures.<br><br>Sustained retraction is far more important than coagulation in initial haemostasis. Failure of retraction (uterine atony) is the commonest cause of postpartum haemorrhage and is treated with uterotonics and uterine massage.<br><br>A (cervical contraction) does not control placental bed bleeding. C (placental clot) is secondary to muscle compression. D (vaginal contraction) does not affect uterine bleeding.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Which stage of labour is most associated with maternal bearing down reflex?',o:['First stage','Third stage','Second stage','Latent phase'],a:2,
    e:`The bearing-down reflex is most prominent in the active second stage, when the fetal head stretches the pelvic floor and vagina, triggering involuntary expulsive contractions and the Valsalva-pushing urge.<br><br>This reflex (Ferguson reflex) increases oxytocin release and supplements uterine contractions with maternal effort. Epidural analgesia can blunt the urge, often delaying diagnosis of the active second stage.<br><br>A (first stage) does not involve bearing down. B (third stage) follows delivery. D (latent phase) is the early part of first stage with no expulsive urge.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological mechanism responsible for progressive descent of the fetus during labour is mainly:',o:['Uterine contractions and maternal pushing','Pelvic ligament relaxation','Placental pressure','Fetal breathing movements'],a:0,
    e:`Progressive fetal descent is driven primarily by uterine contractions during the first stage and passive second stage, supplemented by maternal bearing-down (Valsalva) effort during the active second stage.<br><br>Descent is needed before flexion, internal rotation and extension can occur. Two-fifths or more palpable abdominally indicates the head is not yet engaged; descent through the midpelvis brings the leading point to the ischial spines.<br><br>B (pelvic ligament relaxation) increases capacity but does not propel the fetus. C (placental pressure) is not a driver of descent. D (fetal breathing movements) do not propel the fetus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the lower uterine segment becomes:',o:['Thicker and more contractile','Thinner and more distensible','Rigid and non-distensible','Shorter and thicker'],a:1,
    e:`During labour the lower uterine segment becomes progressively thinner and more distensible as the upper segment retracts. This permits passage of the fetus while the upper segment generates expulsive force.<br><br>The lower segment forms from the isthmus and is largely passive in labour. Excessive thinning in obstructed labour produces a pathological retraction ring (Bandl\'s ring) and predisposes to uterine rupture.<br><br>A (thicker, more contractile) describes the upper segment. C (rigid, non-distensible) is incompatible with normal labour. D (shorter and thicker) is the opposite of what occurs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A sudden gush of blood during the third stage of labour most commonly indicates:',o:['Uterine rupture','Cervical laceration','Fetal distress','Placental separation'],a:3,
    e:`A sudden gush of blood during the third stage is most commonly a sign of placental separation: the retroplacental haematoma is released as the placenta detaches from the decidua basalis.<br><br>Other signs of separation are cord lengthening, the uterus becoming firm and globular, and the fundus rising above the umbilicus. Once separation is confirmed, controlled cord traction is used to deliver the placenta.<br><br>A (uterine rupture) typically presents with severe abdominal pain and maternal collapse, not just a gush. B (cervical laceration) gives continuous bright bleeding. C (fetal distress) is irrelevant after delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The mechanism of placental separation where blood escapes early and placenta separates from edge first is:',o:['Schultze mechanism','Matthews Duncan mechanism','Brandt-Andrews mechanism','Couvelaire mechanism'],a:1,
    e:`The Matthews Duncan mechanism of placental separation begins at the placental margin. Blood escapes early because the cleavage plane opens at the edge first, producing visible bleeding before placental expulsion.<br><br>The placenta presents maternal (rough) surface first at the introitus. The mechanism is less common than Schultze and is more often associated with retained membranes and incomplete separation.<br><br>A (Schultze) separates centrally with concealed bleeding. C (Brandt-Andrews) is a manoeuvre, not a separation pattern. D (Couvelaire) is uterine apoplexy in severe abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The contraction of uterine muscle fibers during labour is mainly mediated by increased intracellular:',o:['Sodium ions','Potassium ions','Calcium ions','Chloride ions'],a:2,
    e:`Myometrial contraction depends on a rise in intracellular free calcium, which binds calmodulin to activate myosin light-chain kinase, allowing actin and myosin filaments to interact and shorten the cell.<br><br>Prostaglandins and oxytocin both increase intracellular calcium influx. Beta-adrenergic agonists and calcium channel blockers oppose this effect, which is the basis for the use of nifedipine and salbutamol as tocolytics.<br><br>A (sodium) does not directly trigger smooth muscle contraction. B (potassium) increase causes hyperpolarisation and relaxation. D (chloride) is not the contraction trigger.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The second stage of labour ends with:',o:['Full cervical dilatation','Delivery of placenta','Rupture of membranes','Delivery of the baby'],a:3,
    e:`The second stage of labour ends with delivery of the fetus. It begins at full cervical dilatation and includes a passive phase before involuntary expulsive contractions and an active phase with maternal pushing.<br><br>Total time to delivery should not exceed 4 hours from full dilatation. Active second stage should be no more than 2 hours in nulliparous and 1 hour in multiparous women without epidural; longer raises maternal and fetal morbidity.<br><br>A (full dilatation) marks the start, not end. B (placenta delivery) ends third stage. C (membrane rupture) does not define stage transition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary physiological role of oxytocin during labour is to:',o:['Stimulate uterine contractions','Initiate fetal descent','Ripen the cervix','Cause placental separation'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin\'s primary role in labour is stimulation of uterine contractions. It binds myometrial receptors that increase intracellular calcium, producing coordinated rhythmic contractions of the upper segment.<br><br>Oxytocin receptor density rises markedly near term, increasing uterine sensitivity. Oxytocin is also released by suckling postpartum, contracting the uterus to limit bleeding and aiding milk let-down via myoepithelial cells.<br><br>B (initiate fetal descent) follows from contractions but is not the primary action. C (cervical ripening) is a prostaglandin effect. D (placental separation) follows uterine retraction after delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the uterine contraction frequency typically becomes:',o:['Less frequent and weaker','More frequent and stronger','Irregular and weak','Absent in second stage'],a:1,
    e:`As labour progresses, uterine contractions become more frequent and stronger, rising from approximately 2 in 10 minutes early in the active phase to 4 to 5 in 10 minutes in advanced labour.<br><br>Each contraction generates an intrauterine pressure of 30 to 60 mmHg, lasting 30 to 60 seconds. Increasing gap junction formation under prostaglandin influence allows progressively more coordinated and powerful activity.<br><br>A (less frequent, weaker) describes pre-labour activity. C (irregular and weak) describes false labour. D (absent in second stage) is incorrect; contractions persist throughout.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The first stage of labour is subdivided into:',o:['Latent and active phases','Early and late phases','Induction and augmentation phases','Pre-labour and labour phases'],a:0,
    e:`The first stage of labour is divided into a latent phase (from labour onset to 3 to 4 cm dilatation) and an active phase (from 4 cm to full dilatation at 10 cm).<br><br>Latent phase typically lasts 3 to 8 hours, during which effacement is completed. Active phase usually lasts 2 to 6 hours with cervical dilatation of about 1 cm per hour. Both phases are shorter in multiparous women.<br><br>B (early and late) is not the standard subdivision. C (induction and augmentation) describes interventions, not phases. D (pre-labour and labour) is informal terminology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin is most commonly used clinically for cervical ripening?',o:['PGE1 (misoprostol)','PGI2','PGF2α','PGE2 (dinoprostone)'],a:3,
    e:`Dinoprostone (PGE2) is the prostaglandin most commonly used clinically for cervical ripening prior to induction of labour, available as vaginal gel, tablet or pessary.<br><br>PGE2 increases cervical proteolytic activity, replaces dermatan sulphate with hyaluronic acid, and increases water content. Misoprostol (PGE1) is also used in some settings, particularly for second-trimester induction and PPH management.<br><br>A (PGE1, misoprostol) is used but PGE2 is the standard for cervical ripening at term. B (PGI2) is prostacyclin, used for pulmonary hypertension. C (PGF2-alpha) is used for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The upper uterine segment during labour is characterized by:',o:['Passive stretching','No muscular activity','Active contraction and retraction','Intermittent relaxation only'],a:2,
    e:`The upper uterine segment during labour is the actively contracting and retracting portion. Each contraction shortens the muscle fibres permanently, producing the thicker upper segment that generates expulsive force.<br><br>This contrasts with the lower segment, which is passive: it stretches, thins and accommodates the descending fetus. The reciprocal action between upper and lower segments is termed polarity of the uterus.<br><br>A (passive stretching) describes the lower segment. B (no muscular activity) is incorrect. D (intermittent relaxation only) misses the retraction component.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the third stage of labour, the placenta is usually delivered within:',o:['30 minutes','15 minutes','5 minutes','60 minutes'],a:0,
    e:`The placenta is normally delivered within 30 minutes of the baby; beyond 30 minutes the third stage is defined as abnormal under active management and the placenta is considered retained.<br><br>With active management most placentas are delivered within 5 to 10 minutes. Manual removal under anaesthesia is required for placentas not delivered within standard timeframes, especially when bleeding is occurring.<br><br>B (15 minutes) is shorter than the upper limit. C (5 minutes) is the typical time, not the upper limit. D (60 minutes) applies only to physiological management.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Which factor primarily triggers the Ferguson reflex?',o:['Uterine fundal contraction','Stretching of cervix and vagina by presenting part','Placental separation','Maternal pain perception'],a:1,
    e:`The Ferguson reflex is triggered by stretching of the cervix and upper vagina by the descending presenting part. Afferent signals reach the spinal cord and stimulate increased oxytocin release from the maternal posterior pituitary.<br><br>This positive feedback loop amplifies labour as it advances: stronger contractions produce more cervical stretch, releasing more oxytocin, producing yet stronger contractions. The reflex also generates the bearing-down urge.<br><br>A (fundal contraction) is the consequence, not the trigger. C (placental separation) is third stage. D (maternal pain) is unrelated to the reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological function of uterine retraction during labour is to:',o:['Increase amniotic fluid pressure','Increase placental blood flow','Relax cervical muscles','Shorten uterine muscle fibers permanently'],a:3,
    e:`The defining function of uterine retraction is permanent shortening of myometrial fibres after each contraction. This is unique to uterine smooth muscle and depends on actin-myosin interactions along the full filament length.<br><br>Retraction creates a thicker, shortened upper segment that generates progressive expulsive force, while compressing placental bed vessels postpartum to prevent haemorrhage. Retraction failure causes uterine atony.<br><br>A (raise amniotic pressure) is unrelated. B (raise placental flow) is opposite (flow falls during contractions). C (relax cervical muscles) is a prostaglandin effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The force generated by uterine contractions during active labour is approximately:',o:['10-20 mmHg','30-50 mmHg','60-80 mmHg','100-120 mmHg'],a:2,
    e:`Active labour contractions generate intrauterine pressures of approximately 30 to 60 mmHg above the resting baseline, and may briefly reach 60 to 80 mmHg in strong contractions in advanced labour.<br><br>Frequency rises from 2 in 10 minutes early on to 4 to 5 in 10 minutes in advanced labour, with each contraction lasting 30 to 60 seconds. Pressures are measured externally with tocography or directly with intrauterine catheters.<br><br>A (10 to 20 mmHg) is the resting tone, not active contraction force. B (30 to 50 mmHg) is the average rather than the active labour peak. D (100 to 120 mmHg) exceeds normal physiological values.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The process by which the fetal head emerges under the pubic symphysis during delivery is called:',o:['Flexion','Extension','Internal rotation','External rotation'],a:1,
    e:`Extension is the cardinal movement by which the well-flexed fetal head emerges under the pubic symphysis. The occiput acts as a fulcrum point as the bregma, face and chin appear in succession over the perineum.<br><br>Extension follows internal rotation. If controlled, it reduces perineal trauma; soft tissue resistance still produces tearing in most first births. The point at which the head no longer recedes between contractions is called crowning.<br><br>A (flexion) presents the smallest head diameter, not the delivery movement. C (internal rotation) precedes extension. D (external rotation) follows delivery of the head.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary mechanism preventing placental retention after delivery is:',o:['Cervical closure','Placental contraction','Uterine contraction and retraction','Umbilical cord shortening'],a:2,
    e:`After placental delivery, sustained uterine contraction and retraction compress the spiral arteries running through the myometrium and prevent retention of placental fragments and ongoing bleeding from the placental bed.<br><br>Active management with intramuscular oxytocin reinforces this contraction-retraction mechanism and reduces postpartum haemorrhage from around 15 percent to 5 percent. Failure of retraction is the leading cause of PPH.<br><br>A (cervical closure) does not prevent retention. B (placental contraction) is not a real mechanism. D (cord shortening) does not retain or expel placenta.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The latent phase of the first stage of labour typically ends when cervical dilatation reaches:',o:['4 cm','2 cm','6 cm','8 cm'],a:0,
    e:`The latent phase of the first stage typically ends when cervical dilatation reaches 3 to 4 cm with full effacement. The active phase then begins, with cervical dilatation usually progressing at 1 cm per hour or more.<br><br>Latent phase duration is variable but usually 3 to 8 hours. Women in latent phase are best managed away from the labour suite, with simple analgesia and reassurance, until the active phase is reached.<br><br>B (2 cm) is mid-latent phase. C (6 cm) is mid active phase. D (8 cm) is late active phase.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The major physiological event marking the end of the third stage of labour is:',o:['Initiation of lactation','Closure of cervix','Cessation of uterine contractions','Delivery of placenta and membranes'],a:3,
    e:`The third stage ends with complete delivery of the placenta and membranes. Inspection of the delivered placenta for missing cotyledons or a succenturiate lobe is essential because retained tissue raises the risk of PPH.<br><br>If retained tissue is suspected, examination under anaesthesia and manual removal of placenta should be arranged. The vulva is then inspected for tears or lacerations needing repair.<br><br>A (lactation initiation) occurs over days postpartum. B (cervical closure) takes weeks. C (cessation of contractions) does not occur; the uterus continues retracting.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological onset of labour is associated with a functional withdrawal of which hormone from the uterus?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Relaxin','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`Functional progesterone withdrawal precedes labour onset. Progesterone receptor expression falls, raising the effective oestrogen-to-progesterone ratio, increasing prostaglandin synthesis, and promoting gap junction formation.<br><br>Without measurable changes in circulating progesterone, the uterus shifts from a state of relaxation to active contractility. Placental CRH, fetal cortisol and oxytocin further support this transition near term.<br><br>B (oxytocin) rises with labour, not withdraws. C (relaxin) softens pelvic ligaments and is not functionally withdrawn. D (prolactin) acts on the breast.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The pacemaker for uterine contractions during labour is usually located in the:',o:['Cervix','Lower uterine segment','Fundus near the cornua','Posterior uterine wall'],a:2,
    e:`The functional uterine pacemaker lies near the cornua at the fundus, where myometrial cells have the greatest spontaneous activity. Contractions originate here and spread downward via gap junctions.<br><br>Although a histologically distinct pacemaker has not been identified, fundal dominance is consistently demonstrated. Gap junctions, formed at term under prostaglandin influence, allow rapid and coordinated electrical spread.<br><br>A (cervix) does not initiate contractions. B (lower segment) is mainly passive. D (posterior wall) is not the typical pacemaker site.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most important physiological effect of uterine retraction during labour is:',o:['Relaxation of cervix','Increased amniotic fluid pressure','Decrease in uterine blood flow','Shortening of uterine muscle fibers permanently'],a:3,
    e:`The defining effect of retraction is permanent shortening of myometrial fibres after each contraction. This builds the thicker upper segment that generates expulsive force and compresses placental bed vessels after delivery.<br><br>Retraction is unique to uterine smooth muscle and depends on actin-myosin interactions along the full filament length. It is reinforced clinically by oxytocin to prevent atonic postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (cervical relaxation) is a prostaglandin effect, not retraction. B (raise amniotic pressure) is not a retraction effect. C (decrease blood flow) occurs during contractions but is not the defining effect of retraction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the first stage of labour, the normal rate of cervical dilatation in primigravida during active phase is approximately:',o:['0.5 cm/hour','1 cm/hour','2 cm/hour','3 cm/hour'],a:1,
    e:`In the active phase of the first stage, cervical dilatation in primigravidae normally proceeds at approximately 1 cm per hour. Less than 1 cm in 2 hours is regarded as abnormally slow progress.<br><br>Multiparous women typically progress faster than 1 cm per hour. Slow progress prompts repeat examination at 2-hourly intervals and consideration of artificial rupture of membranes or oxytocin augmentation.<br><br>A (0.5 cm/hour) is below normal. C (2 cm/hour) is faster than typical. D (3 cm/hour) is precipitate progress.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The lower uterine segment during labour mainly functions to:',o:['Generate uterine contractions','Initiate placental separation','Compress uterine vessels','Stretch and facilitate cervical dilatation'],a:3,
    e:`The lower uterine segment functions to stretch, thin and accommodate the descending fetus, allowing the cervix to be taken up (effaced) into a continuum with the lower segment and facilitating dilatation.<br><br>It is largely passive in labour. The reciprocal action between the actively contracting upper segment and the passive lower segment, called polarity, generates the directional force opening the cervix.<br><br>A (generate contractions) is the upper segment role. B (initiate placental separation) is a third stage event. C (compress vessels) is the role of upper segment retraction postpartum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In the second stage of labour, the urge to bear down occurs primarily due to:',o:['Placental separation','Stretching of pelvic floor and vagina','Increased fetal movements','Maternal pain perception'],a:1,
    e:`The bearing-down urge in the second stage is triggered by stretching of the pelvic floor and vagina by the descending fetal head. This activates the Ferguson reflex and a reflex Valsalva push.<br><br>Pressure on the levator ani muscles produces involuntary expulsive contractions and an irresistible pushing urge. Epidural analgesia blunts the urge by reducing afferent transmission, often delaying recognition of full dilatation.<br><br>A (placental separation) occurs after delivery. C (fetal movements) do not trigger pushing. D (maternal pain) does not specifically generate the bearing-down reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological reason for increased uterine contractility near term is mainly due to increased:',o:['Oxytocin receptors in myometrium','Progesterone receptors','Placental blood flow','Fetal urine production'],a:0,
    e:`Myometrial sensitivity to oxytocin rises near term mainly because oxytocin receptor density increases dramatically in the myometrium and decidua, allowing strong responses to even small amounts of circulating hormone.<br><br>This receptor up-regulation is driven by rising oestrogen and falling effective progesterone activity. Increased gap junction formation under prostaglandin influence further synchronises the myometrial response.<br><br>B (progesterone receptors) fall, not rise. C (placental blood flow) is unrelated to contractility. D (fetal urine) is unrelated to maternal contractility.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most important mechanical factor aiding cervical dilatation in labour is:',o:['Placental pressure','Amniotic fluid pressure alone','Fetal head pressure on cervix','Umbilical cord traction'],a:2,
    e:`Mechanical pressure of the well-flexed fetal head against the cervix is the most important mechanical factor aiding cervical dilatation, transmitting the directional force generated by upper segment contractions.<br><br>An intact bag of forewaters can act as a hydrostatic wedge; once membranes rupture, the head itself takes over. A poorly applied head (malposition or malpresentation) often produces inefficient dilatation despite adequate contractions.<br><br>A (placental pressure) does not aid dilatation. B (amniotic fluid alone) acts only with intact membranes. D (cord traction) is not relevant in first stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The typical duration of the third stage of labour in actively managed labour is usually:',o:['60 minutes','20-30 minutes','45 minutes','Less than 10 minutes'],a:3,
    e:`With active management, the typical third stage lasts under 10 minutes. Intramuscular oxytocin (10 IU) at delivery of the anterior shoulder, controlled cord traction and early or modified cord clamping shorten the third stage and reduce PPH.<br><br>A third stage exceeding 30 minutes under active management is defined as abnormal and the placenta is considered retained. Manual removal under anaesthesia is then required.<br><br>A (60 minutes) is the threshold for physiological management. B (20 to 30 minutes) is the upper limit, not typical. C (45 minutes) exceeds the active management threshold.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological process that causes the uterus to become globular during placental separation is:',o:['Vaginal stretching','Cervical dilatation','Uterine contraction and retraction','Placental detachment alone'],a:2,
    e:`After fetal delivery, continued contraction and retraction reduce uterine volume, expel the placenta, and cause the upper segment to assume a firm globular shape that rises above the umbilicus.<br><br>The change in shape from elongated to globular reflects the empty contracted uterus. A boggy non-globular uterus suggests atony, raises concern for PPH, and is treated with massage and oxytocics.<br><br>A (vaginal stretching) is unrelated to uterine shape. B (cervical dilatation) is a first stage event. D (placental detachment alone) does not in itself produce the shape change without retraction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the fundal dominance of uterine contractions refers to:',o:['Contractions beginning at the fundus and spreading downward','Strongest contractions occurring in the cervix','Lower uterine segment contracting first','Placenta initiating contractions'],a:0,
    e:`Fundal dominance describes the normal pattern of uterine activity in labour: contractions begin at the fundus near the cornua and spread downward toward the lower segment and cervix.<br><br>This pattern is established by the functional fundal pacemaker and rapid spread via gap junctions. Loss of fundal dominance produces dysfunctional, uncoordinated activity and arrest of progress.<br><br>B (strongest at cervix) reverses normal physiology. C (lower segment first) is incorrect. D (placenta initiates) is not how contractions originate.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The mechanism that allows the fetal head to navigate the maternal pelvis by changing its shape is called:',o:['Flexion','Moulding','Engagement','Extension'],a:1,
    e:`Moulding is the change in fetal head shape during labour produced by overlapping of the parietal bones over the frontal and occipital bones, made possible by unossified sutures and compressible bones.<br><br>Moulding reduces the diameters of the fetal head and helps it negotiate the bony pelvis while still protecting the underlying brain. Severe or early moulding can be a sign of obstructed labour or cephalopelvic disproportion.<br><br>A (flexion) is a cardinal movement, not skull deformation. C (engagement) is descent of the head into the pelvic brim. D (extension) is a delivery movement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The cardinal movement of labour that reduces the presenting diameter of the fetal head is:',o:['Flexion','Internal rotation','Extension','External rotation'],a:0,
    e:`Flexion is the cardinal movement that brings the chin onto the chest, allowing the smallest longitudinal diameter (suboccipito-bregmatic, 9.5 cm) to present to the maternal pelvis.<br><br>Flexion is a passive movement caused by the head meeting the resistance of the pelvic walls and pelvic floor. A poorly flexed head presents larger diameters such as occipito-frontal (11.5 cm), prolonging labour.<br><br>B (internal rotation) reorients the head, not its diameter. C (extension) increases the diameter at delivery. D (external rotation) follows delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological increase in prostaglandins near term primarily results in:',o:['Placental growth','Increased fetal movement','Cervical ripening and uterine contractions','Decreased uterine sensitivity'],a:2,
    e:`Prostaglandin synthesis by the chorion and decidua rises near term, producing two main effects: cervical ripening (softening, shortening, increased water content) and increased myometrial contractility through calcium influx.<br><br>Prostaglandins also stimulate gap junction formation between myometrial cells, allowing coordinated activity. PGE2 and PGF2-alpha are the principal mediators, and synthetic PGE2 is used clinically for cervical ripening.<br><br>A (placental growth) is not a prostaglandin effect. B (fetal movement) is unrelated. D (decreased uterine sensitivity) is the opposite of the actual effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, uterine contractions normally occur at intervals of:',o:['Every 10-15 minutes','Every 2-3 minutes in active labour','Every 20 minutes','Every 30 minutes'],a:1,
    e:`In active labour, contractions typically occur at intervals of 2 to 4 minutes, described in terms of frequency in a 10-minute window: 4 to 5 in 10 minutes is usually considered ideal in advanced labour.<br><br>Each contraction lasts 30 to 60 seconds with intrauterine pressure of 30 to 60 mmHg. Inadequate frequency raises suspicion of dysfunctional uterine activity, which may respond to artificial rupture of membranes or oxytocin.<br><br>A (every 10 to 15 minutes) is too infrequent for active labour. C (every 20 minutes) suggests latent phase. D (every 30 minutes) is consistent with pre-labour activity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The mechanism of placental separation associated with concealed bleeding is:',o:['Bandl mechanism','Matthews Duncan mechanism','Couvelaire mechanism','Schultze mechanism'],a:3,
    e:`The Schultze mechanism, the most common pattern of placental separation, begins centrally with formation of a retroplacental haematoma that remains concealed behind the placenta until expulsion is complete.<br><br>External bleeding is minimal until after the placenta delivers, fetal surface first. The Matthews Duncan pattern, by contrast, separates from the margin first, allowing earlier visible blood loss before placental delivery.<br><br>A (Bandl) refers to a pathological retraction ring, not separation. B (Matthews Duncan) is associated with early external bleeding. C (Couvelaire) is uterine apoplexy in severe abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological basis of the "living ligature" mechanism preventing postpartum hemorrhage is:',o:['Cervical constriction','Placental clot formation','Uterine muscle fibers compressing blood vessels','Vaginal contraction'],a:2,
    e:`The living-ligature mechanism describes how the lattice-arranged myometrial fibres of the upper segment, on retracting around spiral arteries that pierce the wall, compress these vessels and arrest bleeding from the placental bed.<br><br>This mechanical occlusion is the primary postpartum haemostatic mechanism, far more important than coagulation. Failure of retraction (uterine atony) leaves vessels open and is the leading cause of postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (cervical constriction) plays no role in placental bed haemostasis. B (placental clot) is secondary to muscle compression. D (vaginal contraction) does not control uterine bleeding.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The part of uterus that undergoes the greatest retraction during labour is the:',o:['Cervix','Upper uterine segment','Lower uterine segment','Broad ligament'],a:1,
    e:`The upper uterine segment undergoes the greatest retraction during labour. Its myometrial fibres permanently shorten after each contraction, building a thicker actively contracting upper segment.<br><br>This polarity (active retracting upper segment, passive distensible lower segment) generates the directional force that opens the cervix and propels the fetus. The lower segment thins and stretches but does not retract.<br><br>A (cervix) does not retract; it effaces and dilates. C (lower segment) is passive. D (broad ligament) contains no contractile myometrium.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The typical pressure generated during strong uterine contractions in labour may reach:',o:['10 mmHg','20 mmHg','50 mmHg','100 mmHg'],a:3,
    e:`During strong active labour contractions, intrauterine pressure can rise sharply above the typical 30 to 60 mmHg average, occasionally approaching 100 mmHg, particularly during the late first and active second stages.<br><br>Pressure rises during expulsion are augmented further by maternal Valsalva pushing in the second stage. Excessive frequency or pressure (tachysystole or hyperstimulation) reduces uteroplacental perfusion and may compromise the fetus.<br><br>A (10 mmHg) and B (20 mmHg) are within resting tone. C (50 mmHg) is the upper end of the average range, not the strong contraction peak.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological mechanism that ensures progressive descent of the fetus during labour is:',o:['Uterine retraction','Cervical effacement','Placental pressure','Maternal tachycardia'],a:0,
    e:`Uterine retraction ensures that progress is unidirectional: each contraction shortens upper segment fibres so the fetus does not slip back when the contraction ends. Successive contractions thus drive cumulative descent.<br><br>Without retraction, the fetus would return to its starting position after each contraction and labour would not progress. Retraction also builds the thicker upper segment that generates expulsive force in the second stage.<br><br>B (cervical effacement) is a parallel process, not the descent driver. C (placental pressure) does not propel the fetus. D (maternal tachycardia) is unrelated to descent.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The major role of relaxin during pregnancy and labour is:',o:['Stimulate uterine contractions','Relax pelvic ligaments and cervix','Increase fetal heart rate','Promote placental separation'],a:1,
    e:`Relaxin softens the pelvic ligaments at the pubic ramus and sacroiliac joints in late pregnancy, increasing pelvic flexibility, and contributes to cervical softening through extracellular matrix remodelling.<br><br>Increased ligament laxity may allow pelvic dimensions to expand during labour, an effect enhanced by upright maternal positions such as squatting. Relaxin acts alongside prostaglandins, which are the principal cervical ripening agents.<br><br>A (stimulate contractions) is the role of oxytocin. C (raise fetal heart rate) is unrelated to relaxin. D (placental separation) follows uterine retraction, not relaxin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common presenting diameter of the fetal head in normal vertex presentation is:',o:['Suboccipitobregmatic diameter','Occipitofrontal diameter','Biparietal diameter','Mentovertical diameter'],a:0,
    e:`In a well-flexed vertex presentation the suboccipito-bregmatic diameter (9.5 cm) is presented to the maternal pelvis. This is the smallest longitudinal diameter, measured from beneath the occiput to the centre of the anterior fontanelle.<br><br>Flexion brings the chin onto the chest. A poorly flexed head presents larger diameters: suboccipito-frontal (10 cm), occipito-frontal (11.5 cm) or mento-vertical (13 cm), with the last too large for normal pelvic passage.<br><br>B (occipitofrontal) presents in a deflexed OP head. C (biparietal) is the transverse diameter. D (mentovertical) is the brow presentation diameter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the lower uterine segment forms primarily from:',o:['Body of uterus','Cervical canal','Isthmus of uterus','Broad ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The lower uterine segment forms primarily from the isthmus of the uterus, the narrow region between the body of the uterus above and the cervix below, which expands progressively as pregnancy advances.<br><br>By term, the isthmus has elongated and thinned to form a distensible lower segment. During labour, retraction of the upper segment further stretches it, and effacement incorporates the cervix into a continuum with the lower segment.<br><br>A (body) forms the upper segment. B (cervical canal) is incorporated by effacement, not the source. D (broad ligament) is a peritoneal fold, not myometrial.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological advantage of moulding of the fetal head during labour is:',o:['Prevents fetal hypoxia','Prevents placental separation','Reduces uterine contractions','Allows fetal head to adapt to pelvic dimensions'],a:3,
    e:`Moulding allows the fetal skull bones to overlap at unossified sutures, reducing skull diameters and helping the head adapt to the maternal pelvis while still protecting the underlying brain.<br><br>The parietal bones typically slide over the frontal and occipital bones. Severe or early moulding can be a sign of obstructed labour from malposition or cephalopelvic disproportion, and persistent severe moulding warrants reassessment.<br><br>A (prevent fetal hypoxia) is unrelated to moulding. B (prevent placental separation) is irrelevant. C (reduce contractions) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The Ferguson reflex results in increased secretion of:',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`The Ferguson reflex increases secretion of oxytocin from the maternal posterior pituitary in response to stretching of the cervix and upper vagina by the descending presenting part.<br><br>This positive feedback loop amplifies contractions as labour advances. Greater oxytocin produces stronger contractions, more cervical stretch, and yet more oxytocin release. The reflex also contributes to the maternal urge to bear down.<br><br>B (progesterone) is functionally withdrawn before labour. C (estrogen) is not released by the Ferguson reflex. D (prolactin) acts on the breast, not the uterus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the second stage of labour, descent of the fetus occurs mainly due to:',o:['Placental contraction','Cervical dilatation','Maternal pushing and uterine contractions','Amniotic fluid pressure alone'],a:2,
    e:`Fetal descent in the active second stage results from the combined action of uterine contractions and maternal voluntary bearing-down (Valsalva) efforts. Maternal pushing supplements the involuntary uterine force.<br><br>In the passive second stage, descent occurs from contractions alone, allowing rotation before active pushing. Epidural analgesia can blunt the urge to push, prolonging this stage and influencing decisions about timing of delivery.<br><br>A (placental contraction) does not occur. B (cervical dilatation) is complete by second stage. D (amniotic fluid pressure) is gone after rupture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common cause of prolonged third stage of labour is:',o:['Placenta previa','Retained placenta','Fetal distress','Maternal hypotension'],a:1,
    e:`Retained placenta is the most common cause of a prolonged third stage. About 2 percent of placentas are not expelled by controlled cord traction and require manual removal under anaesthesia.<br><br>Risk factors include previous uterine surgery, placenta accreta, prolonged labour and oxytocin use. A third stage longer than 30 minutes under active management or 60 minutes with physiological management defines retention.<br><br>A (placenta praevia) is a pre-delivery diagnosis. C (fetal distress) is irrelevant after delivery. D (maternal hypotension) is a consequence, not a cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The cardinal movement that occurs immediately before delivery of the head is:',o:['Internal rotation','Descent','Flexion','Extension'],a:3,
    e:`Extension is the cardinal movement immediately preceding delivery of the head. The well-flexed head, having completed internal rotation, extends around the pubic symphysis as the occiput emerges from beneath it.<br><br>The occiput acts as a fulcrum, and the bregma, face and chin then sweep over the perineum in succession. Controlled extension limits perineal trauma; soft-tissue resistance still produces some tearing in most first births.<br><br>A (internal rotation) precedes extension. B (descent) is continuous and overlaps multiple movements. C (flexion) precedes internal rotation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological hormone surge in the fetus that contributes to onset of labour is mainly:',o:['Fetal insulin','Fetal prolactin','Fetal cortisol','Fetal growth hormone'],a:2,
    e:`Fetal cortisol from the maturing fetal adrenal gland rises near term and contributes to the hormonal cascade initiating labour by stimulating placental conversion of progesterone to oestrogen and increasing prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Placental CRH also rises towards term and potentiates the action of prostaglandins and oxytocin on the myometrium. Fetal pituitary oxytocin secretion adds further to the hormonal milieu favouring labour onset.<br><br>A (fetal insulin) is unrelated to labour onset. B (fetal prolactin) is not part of this cascade. D (fetal growth hormone) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine segment that becomes progressively thinner during labour is the:',o:['Lower uterine segment','Upper uterine segment','Fundus','Cervical canal'],a:0,
    e:`The lower uterine segment becomes progressively thinner during labour as the upper segment retracts. Thinning is necessary to accommodate the descending fetus and allow the cervix to be taken up into a continuum with it.<br><br>Excessive thinning in obstructed labour produces a pathological retraction ring (Bandl ring), a transverse ridge palpable on the abdomen that signals impending uterine rupture if the obstruction is not relieved.<br><br>B (upper segment) becomes thicker, not thinner. C (fundus) is part of the upper segment. D (cervical canal) effaces but does not thin in this sense.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most reliable physiological indicator of effective uterine contractions is:',o:['Maternal tachycardia','Progressive cervical dilatation','Increased fetal movement','Vaginal bleeding'],a:1,
    e:`Progressive cervical dilatation is the most reliable physiological indicator of effective uterine contractions. In active first stage, dilatation should normally proceed at approximately 1 cm per hour or more.<br><br>Less than 1 cm in 2 hours is regarded as abnormally slow progress. Strong contractions without cervical change suggest dysfunctional polarity, malposition, malpresentation or cephalopelvic disproportion, requiring reassessment.<br><br>A (maternal tachycardia) is non-specific. C (fetal movement) does not indicate contraction effectiveness. D (vaginal bleeding) is abnormal and not a marker of contraction quality.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, uterine contractions are coordinated by electrical signals spreading through:',o:['Pelvic nerves','Cervical nerves','Placental circulation','Gap junctions between myometrial cells'],a:3,
    e:`Coordination of uterine contractions during labour depends on gap junctions, low-resistance electrical connections between myometrial cells that allow rapid spread of action potentials throughout the myometrium.<br><br>Gap junctions are scarce in early pregnancy and form in significant numbers at term under prostaglandin influence. Their absence in pre-term labour contributes to less coordinated, less effective contractions.<br><br>A (pelvic nerves) carry sensation, not contraction signals. B (cervical nerves) play no role in coordination. C (placental circulation) does not transmit electrical signals.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological benefit of amniotic fluid during labour is mainly:',o:['Prevent fetal infection','Increase placental perfusion','Form hydrostatic wedge aiding cervical dilatation','Reduce uterine contractions'],a:2,
    e:`The intact bag of forewaters acts as a hydrostatic wedge, transmitting the pressure of uterine contractions evenly to the cervix and assisting cervical dilatation in the early first stage of labour.<br><br>Once membranes rupture, the well-applied fetal head replaces the wedge and continues to drive dilatation. Premature rupture before adequate cervical change can result in a poorly applied head and inefficient progress.<br><br>A (prevent infection) is true generally but not the labour role. B (raise placental perfusion) is the opposite of contraction effects. D (reduce contractions) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal movement occurring after delivery of the head that aligns shoulders with pelvic outlet is:',o:['Flexion','Internal rotation','Engagement','Restitution'],a:3,
    e:`Restitution is the slight rotation of the fetal head through one-eighth of a circle that occurs immediately after delivery of the head, realigning it with the shoulders still inside the birth canal.<br><br>Restitution is followed by external rotation, in which the shoulders rotate to the AP plane (the widest at the outlet) and the head rotates a further one-eighth, allowing the anterior shoulder to deliver under the pubic symphysis.<br><br>A (flexion) is the diameter-reducing pre-delivery movement. B (internal rotation) precedes head delivery. C (engagement) occurs at the pelvic inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The stage of labour most associated with risk of postpartum hemorrhage is:',o:['First stage','Third stage','Second stage','Latent phase'],a:1,
    e:`The third stage carries the greatest risk of postpartum haemorrhage because the placenta separates and the placental bed bleeds until uterine retraction compresses the spiral arteries.<br><br>Active management with intramuscular oxytocin and controlled cord traction reduces PPH from approximately 15 percent to 5 percent. Uterine atony, retained tissue and trauma are the main causes when retraction fails.<br><br>A (first stage) does not involve placental separation bleeding. C (second stage) bleeding is usually minimal. D (latent phase) is part of first stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The hormone primarily responsible for milk ejection reflex postpartum is:',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Cortisol'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin from the maternal posterior pituitary is responsible for milk ejection (the let-down reflex). Suckling stimulates pulsatile oxytocin release, which contracts myoepithelial cells around alveoli and along lactiferous ducts.<br><br>The reflex can also be triggered by visual, olfactory or auditory cues such as hearing the baby cry, but is inhibited by stress. Oxytocin also produces uterine after-pains during early breastfeeding.<br><br>B (oestrogen) is not the let-down hormone. C (progesterone) inhibits lactation antenatally. D (cortisol) supports milk synthesis but does not eject milk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common physiological cause of failure of placental separation is:',o:['Cervical stenosis','Uterine atony','Placenta previa','Maternal anemia'],a:1,
    e:`Failure of placental separation results most commonly from inadequate uterine contraction and retraction (uterine atony). Without sufficient reduction in uterine volume, the cleavage plane in the decidua basalis does not develop fully.<br><br>Atony is more likely after prolonged or augmented labour, multiple pregnancy, polyhydramnios and a precipitous delivery. Active management with oxytocin reinforces retraction and reduces both retention and postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (cervical stenosis) is not a typical cause. C (placenta praevia) is anatomical, not a separation cause. D (anaemia) does not cause retention.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the third stage of labour, controlled cord traction is performed after:',o:['Uterine relaxation','Cervical dilatation','Signs of placental separation','Fetal head engagement'],a:2,
    e:`Controlled cord traction is performed only after signs of placental separation are recognised: cord lengthening, a small gush of blood, the uterus becoming firm and globular, and the fundus rising above the umbilicus.<br><br>Pulling on the cord before separation risks uterine inversion, particularly if the suprapubic hand does not adequately support the uterus. Traction must be smooth and accompanied by guarding of the uterus.<br><br>A (uterine relaxation) is the wrong moment for traction. B (cervical dilatation) belongs to first stage. D (head engagement) belongs to first stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine muscle layer responsible for powerful contractions in labour is:',o:['Perimetrium','Decidua','Endometrium','Myometrium'],a:3,
    e:`The myometrium, the thick middle muscular layer of the uterus, generates the powerful contractions of labour. Its smooth muscle cells, arranged in a lattice through extracellular matrix, contract in response to oxytocin and prostaglandins.<br><br>Contractions originate at the fundal pacemaker and spread via gap junctions, with the upper segment thickening through retraction and the lower segment passively distending. The endometrium and serosal perimetrium do not contract.<br><br>A (perimetrium) is the outer serosa. B (decidua) is gestational endometrium. C (endometrium) is the lining, not contractile.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological trigger for maternal urge to push is mainly:',o:['Pressure of presenting part on pelvic floor','Cervical stretching','Placental separation','Fetal movements'],a:0,
    e:`The maternal urge to push arises mainly from pressure of the descending presenting part on the pelvic floor and lower vagina, triggering reflex involuntary expulsive contractions and the Valsalva pushing reflex.<br><br>The Ferguson reflex amplifies oxytocin release in response to cervical and vaginal stretch. Together these mechanisms make the urge irresistible. Epidural analgesia can blunt the urge by reducing afferent transmission.<br><br>B (cervical stretching) contributes to oxytocin release but the bearing-down urge specifically depends on pelvic floor pressure. C (placental separation) is a third stage event. D (fetal movements) do not trigger pushing.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common presentation in normal labour is:',o:['Breech','Face','Vertex','Brow'],a:2,
    e:`The vertex presentation is by far the most common in normal labour. The vertex is the area of the fetal skull bounded by the parietal eminences and the anterior and posterior fontanelles.<br><br>In a flexed occipito-anterior vertex with a gynaecoid pelvis, the smallest suboccipito-bregmatic diameter (9.5 cm) presents and outcomes are most favourable for spontaneous vaginal birth. Other presentations are less common and often require intervention.<br><br>A (breech) occurs in around 3 percent at term. B (face) is rare. D (brow) is also rare and typically too large to deliver vaginally without conversion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological mechanism responsible for progressive shortening of cervix during labour is:',o:['Effacement','Dilatation','Engagement','Extension'],a:0,
    e:`Effacement is the progressive shortening of the cervix as it is taken up into the lower uterine segment. By the end of effacement the cervix is fully thinned and continuous with the lower segment.<br><br>Effacement is driven by retraction of upper-segment myometrial fibres and is usually expressed as a percentage. In primigravidae effacement precedes significant dilatation; in multiparous women they tend to occur simultaneously.<br><br>B (dilatation) is opening of the os, not shortening. C (engagement) is descent of the head. D (extension) is a delivery cardinal movement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, uterine blood flow temporarily decreases during:',o:['Relaxation phase','Uterine contraction','Placental separation','Cervical dilatation'],a:1,
    e:`Uterine blood flow falls during each contraction because compression of the spiral arteries by contracted myometrium reduces perfusion of the intervillous space.<br><br>A healthy term fetus tolerates these intermittent reductions because of fetal haemoglobin\'s high oxygen affinity, the placental reserve and a switch to anaerobic metabolism if needed. Pre-existing fetal compromise worsens with each contraction.<br><br>A (relaxation phase) restores flow. C (placental separation) is a third stage event. D (cervical dilatation) does not directly alter perfusion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological purpose of retraction during labour is to:',o:['Prevent uterine rupture','Prevent fetal descent','Increase placental perfusion','Maintain progress of labour by preventing backward movement'],a:3,
    e:`Retraction prevents fetal slippage backwards between contractions, ensuring that each contraction\'s gain in descent is preserved. Successive contractions thus produce cumulative progress through the birth canal.<br><br>Permanent shortening of upper-segment fibres after each contraction also builds the thicker upper segment that generates expulsive force, and after delivery, sustained retraction compresses placental bed vessels.<br><br>A (prevent rupture) is the opposite; excessive retraction without descent produces Bandl ring. B (prevent descent) is incorrect; retraction promotes it. C (raise placental flow) is the opposite of contraction effects.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The mechanism responsible for delivery of shoulders after head is called:',o:['External rotation','Flexion','Internal rotation','Engagement'],a:0,
    e:`External rotation, the cardinal movement following restitution, brings the shoulders into the AP diameter of the pelvic outlet, the widest diameter at this level, allowing the anterior shoulder to deliver under the pubic symphysis.<br><br>After external rotation the head appears transverse to the maternal axis. Gentle downward traction releases the anterior shoulder, then upward traction guides the posterior shoulder over the perineum.<br><br>B (flexion) reduces head diameter, not shoulder rotation. C (internal rotation) reorients the head, not shoulders. D (engagement) is at the pelvic inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary physiological factor that increases uterine excitability near term is increased:',o:['Progesterone activity','Placental growth hormone','Maternal insulin','Estrogen-to-progesterone ratio'],a:3,
    e:`Uterine excitability rises near term primarily through a fall in effective progesterone activity and a rise in oestrogen, increasing the oestrogen-to-progesterone ratio and removing progesterone\'s inhibition of contractions.<br><br>Functional progesterone withdrawal increases prostaglandin synthesis, gap junction formation and oxytocin receptor density. Together these prepare the myometrium for coordinated, sustained labour activity.<br><br>A (progesterone activity) actually decreases. B (placental growth hormone) is unrelated to contractility. C (maternal insulin) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The main function of the pelvic floor muscles during the second stage is to:',o:['Stop fetal descent','Reduce uterine contractions','Guide rotation of fetal head','Prevent cervical dilatation'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic floor muscles, formed by the levator ani and their fascia, create a gutter-shaped sling that guides the fetal head to flex and rotate anteriorly as it descends through the midpelvis to the outlet.<br><br>This anatomical configuration encourages the occiput to rotate to the front (occipito-anterior) and the sagittal suture to lie in the AP diameter at the outlet. The perineum then resists delivery and is stretched as the head crowns.<br><br>A (stop descent) is incorrect. B (reduce contractions) is unrelated to pelvic floor. D (prevent dilatation) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The final step of the third stage of labour is:',o:['Placental separation','Delivery of placenta and membranes','Uterine contraction','Cervical closure'],a:1,
    e:`The third stage ends with complete delivery of the placenta and membranes. Inspection follows to confirm that no cotyledons or succenturiate lobes are missing, since retained tissue raises the risk of postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>Suspected retention warrants examination under anaesthesia and manual removal. Genital tract inspection for tears or lacerations follows, and significant trauma requires repair under appropriate analgesia.<br><br>A (placental separation) precedes delivery. C (uterine contraction) continues throughout. D (cervical closure) takes weeks postpartum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological response immediately after delivery of placenta is:',o:['Sustained uterine contraction','Uterine atony','Cervical dilatation','Increased fetal heart rate'],a:0,
    e:`After placental delivery the uterus continues with sustained contraction and retraction. This compresses the spiral arteries running through the myometrium and rapidly reduces blood loss from the placental bed.<br><br>Persistent contraction is reinforced clinically by intramuscular oxytocin given at delivery of the anterior shoulder. Failure of sustained contraction (uterine atony) is the leading cause of postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>B (atony) is the abnormal opposite. C (cervical dilatation) belongs to first stage. D (raised fetal heart rate) is irrelevant after delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The major physiological purpose of uterine contractions during labour is to:',o:['Deliver placenta first','Increase maternal blood pressure','Dilate cervix and expel fetus','Prevent fetal movements'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine contractions during labour exist to dilate the cervix and expel the fetus. The first stage opens the cervix; the second stage propels the fetus through the birth canal.<br><br>Coordinated upper-segment contractions with retraction generate the directional force, while a passive distending lower segment and ripening cervix permit progress. Maternal Valsalva pushing supplements this in the active second stage.<br><br>A (deliver placenta first) is the third stage role. B (raise blood pressure) is incidental. D (prevent fetal movements) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A 26-year-old primigravida at 39 weeks presents in labour. Cervix is 5 cm dilated, membranes intact, and contractions occur every 3 minutes lasting 45 seconds. Which phase of the first stage of labour is she most likely in?',o:['Latent phase','Second stage','Transitional phase','Active phase'],a:3,
    e:`At 5 cm dilatation with regular strong contractions every 3 minutes, the woman is in the active phase of the first stage of labour, which begins around 3 to 4 cm and continues to full dilatation at 10 cm.<br><br>Active phase is characterised by progressive cervical dilatation of approximately 1 cm per hour or more in a primigravida and contractions of increasing frequency and intensity. Latent phase precedes active phase and involves effacement.<br><br>A (latent phase) usually ends by 4 cm. B (second stage) begins at full dilatation. C (transitional phase) is not a standard category.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida in labour has cervical dilation of 3 cm with mild irregular contractions. Which physiological process predominates at this stage?',o:['Rapid fetal descent','Cervical effacement','Placental separation','Shoulder rotation'],a:1,
    e:`At 3 cm dilatation with mild irregular contractions, the woman is in the latent phase of the first stage. The dominant physiological process is cervical effacement: shortening and thinning as the cervix is taken up into the lower segment.<br><br>In primigravidae, effacement is usually complete before significant dilatation. The latent phase typically lasts 3 to 8 hours and ends when dilatation reaches 3 to 4 cm and the cervix is fully effaced.<br><br>A (rapid descent) belongs to second stage. C (placental separation) is third stage. D (shoulder rotation) is post-delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old primigravida has been in labour for 10 hours. Cervical dilation progressed from 4 cm to 6 cm in 2 hours. According to expected physiology of labour, this pattern indicates:',o:['Secondary arrest of labour','Prolonged latent phase','Normal progress of labour','Obstructed labour'],a:2,
    e:`Cervical dilatation from 4 to 6 cm in 2 hours is exactly 1 cm per hour, which is the lower limit of normal active phase progress in a primigravida. This represents normal labour progress.<br><br>Progress is considered abnormally slow only if dilatation is less than 1 cm in 2 hours. Repeat vaginal examination is then indicated, and if delay is confirmed, artificial rupture of membranes or oxytocin augmentation may be considered.<br><br>A (secondary arrest) requires no progress, not 1 cm/hour. B (prolonged latent phase) is for under 4 cm. D (obstructed labour) usually shows no progress and a deflexed or malpositioned head.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A multiparous woman in labour suddenly feels an intense urge to push. Vaginal examination shows full cervical dilatation and fetal head at +2 station. Which physiological reflex is responsible?',o:['Hegar reflex','Valsalva reflex','Moro reflex','Ferguson reflex'],a:3,
    e:`An intense urge to push at full dilatation with the head at +2 station is mediated by the Ferguson reflex: stretching of the cervix and upper vagina reflexly increases oxytocin release from the maternal posterior pituitary.<br><br>The reflex amplifies contractions and triggers involuntary bearing-down efforts. It depends on intact afferent transmission, which is why epidural analgesia can blunt the urge and delay diagnosis of the active second stage.<br><br>A (Hegar) is a pregnancy sign at the isthmus. B (Valsalva) is the manoeuvre, not the trigger reflex. C (Moro) is a neonatal startle reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour monitoring, uterine contractions are recorded as 3 contractions every 10 minutes, each lasting 60 seconds. Which stage of labour is most consistent with this pattern?',o:['Active phase of first stage','Latent phase','Third stage','Immediate postpartum period'],a:0,
    e:`Three contractions every 10 minutes lasting 60 seconds is the typical pattern of the active phase of the first stage of labour, with frequency rising to 4 to 5 in 10 minutes in advanced labour.<br><br>Each contraction generates an intrauterine pressure of 30 to 60 mmHg with this pattern producing progressive cervical dilatation of around 1 cm per hour in a primigravida.<br><br>B (latent phase) typically has fewer, milder contractions. C (third stage) follows fetal delivery. D (immediate postpartum) does not have measured contractions in this way.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida reaches full cervical dilatation. Despite good contractions, the fetal head remains above the pelvic inlet. Which physiological event must occur before descent?',o:['Extension','Engagement','External rotation','Placental separation'],a:1,
    e:`Engagement, the first cardinal movement, must occur before descent through the pelvis can proceed. The widest part of the presenting part has passed through the pelvic inlet, with no more than two-fifths of the fetal head palpable abdominally.<br><br>In nulliparous women engagement usually happens by 37 weeks; in multiparous women it often does not occur until labour begins. Failure to engage at full dilatation suggests cephalopelvic disproportion or malposition.<br><br>A (extension) is a delivery movement. C (external rotation) follows restitution after head delivery. D (placental separation) is third stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, flexion of the fetal head allows the smallest diameter to present. Which diameter is presented in a well-flexed vertex?',o:['Suboccipitobregmatic','Biparietal','Occipitofrontal','Mentovertical'],a:0,
    e:`In a well-flexed vertex, the presenting diameter is the suboccipito-bregmatic, measuring 9.5 cm from beneath the occiput to the centre of the anterior fontanelle. This is the smallest longitudinal diameter of the fetal head.<br><br>Flexion is a passive movement caused by the head meeting pelvic resistance and is essential for normal progress. A poorly flexed head presents larger diameters such as occipito-frontal (11.5 cm), prolonging labour.<br><br>B (biparietal, 9.5 cm transverse) is a transverse measurement. C (occipitofrontal) is a deflexed diameter. D (mentovertical) is a brow presentation diameter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A labouring woman suddenly has a gush of blood and the umbilical cord lengthens. Which event most likely occurred?',o:['Uterine rupture','Placental separation','Cervical tear','Amniotic fluid leak'],a:1,
    e:`A sudden gush of blood combined with apparent lengthening of the umbilical cord at the introitus is a classic sign of placental separation in the third stage of labour.<br><br>Other supporting signs include the uterus becoming firm and globular and the fundus rising above the umbilicus. Once these are confirmed, controlled cord traction can deliver the separated placenta safely.<br><br>A (uterine rupture) typically presents with severe pain and maternal collapse. C (cervical tear) gives continuous bleeding without cord change. D (amniotic leak) precedes delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'After delivery of the baby, the uterus becomes firm, globular, and rises in the abdomen. What physiological event is occurring?',o:['Cervical contraction','Vaginal contraction','Placental separation','Uterine rupture'],a:2,
    e:`After delivery, a uterus that becomes firm and globular and rises in the abdomen is showing classic signs of placental separation. The change occurs as the placenta detaches and descends into the lower segment.<br><br>Other signs are cord lengthening and a small gush of blood. Confirmation of separation precedes safe controlled cord traction; pulling before separation risks uterine inversion and haemorrhage.<br><br>A (cervical contraction) does not cause this finding. B (vaginal contraction) is unrelated. D (uterine rupture) presents with collapse and severe pain.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida in the second stage of labour has the fetal head visible at the introitus during contractions but it disappears between contractions. This sign represents:',o:['Crowning','Engagement','Caput succedaneum','Descent'],a:3,
    e:`The fetal head appearing at the introitus during contractions but receding between them is descent within the second stage. Crowning, by contrast, is when the head no longer recedes between contractions.<br><br>Once the head crowns, delivery is imminent: the head has passed through the pelvic floor and the perineum is fully stretched. The hands-on technique can then control the speed of head delivery to limit trauma.<br><br>A (crowning) requires the head to remain visible between contractions. B (engagement) is at the pelvic inlet, not the vulva. C (caput succedaneum) is scalp oedema, not visible movement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Uterine contractions normally start at the fundus and spread downward toward the cervix. This pattern reflects:',o:['Uterine polarity','Cervical ripening','Pelvic floor resistance','Placental perfusion'],a:0,
    e:`Contractions starting at the fundus and spreading downward to the cervix is the pattern called fundal dominance, a feature of normal uterine polarity in labour.<br><br>The functional pacemaker lies near the cornua and electrical signals propagate via gap junctions. The upper segment retracts and contracts strongly while the lower segment relaxes and stretches, producing the directional expulsive force.<br><br>B (cervical ripening) is a separate process. C (pelvic floor resistance) shapes head rotation, not contractions. D (placental perfusion) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the fetal head becomes more flexed to facilitate passage through the pelvis. Which muscle tone contributes most to this movement?',o:['Pelvic floor muscles','Cervical muscles','Abdominal muscles','Uterine fundal contractions'],a:3,
    e:`Flexion of the fetal head during labour is a passive movement caused mainly by uterine fundal contractions driving the head against pelvic resistance. The head meets the pelvic walls and floor and naturally flexes.<br><br>Flexion brings the chin onto the chest and presents the smallest suboccipito-bregmatic diameter (9.5 cm) to the maternal pelvis. The configuration of the bony pelvis and the levator sling further encourages flexion.<br><br>A (pelvic floor muscles) help internal rotation, not flexion as such. B (cervical muscles) play no role. C (abdominal muscles) supplement bearing-down in second stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During vaginal examination, the sagittal suture lies in the transverse diameter of the pelvis at the pelvic inlet. This finding indicates:',o:['Internal rotation','Engagement','Extension','External rotation'],a:1,
    e:`When the fetal head enters the pelvis with its sagittal suture in the transverse diameter at the inlet, this corresponds to engagement, the first cardinal movement of labour.<br><br>The transverse diameter is the widest at the pelvic inlet (13.5 cm), so the head naturally enters in this orientation. Internal rotation later brings the sagittal suture into the AP diameter at the outlet, where AP is widest.<br><br>A (internal rotation) reorients to AP at the outlet. C (extension) is a delivery movement. D (external rotation) follows head delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus in persistent occipito-posterior position usually rotates during labour to occipito-anterior. Which movement achieves this?',o:['Flexion','Extension','Internal rotation','Restitution'],a:2,
    e:`An occipito-posterior fetus that rotates to occipito-anterior during labour does so by internal rotation, the cardinal movement guided by the gutter-shaped pelvic floor as the head descends through the midpelvis.<br><br>OP rotation can be the long-arc rotation through 135 degrees, explaining the increased duration of labour in OP positions. Persistent OP may result in face-to-pubes delivery, prolonged labour or instrumental delivery.<br><br>A (flexion) reduces head diameter. B (extension) is a delivery movement. D (restitution) follows head delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida experiences a prolonged second stage despite full cervical dilatation. Which force most significantly contributes to fetal expulsion at this stage?',o:['Uterine retraction alone','Placental contraction','Cervical dilation','Maternal bearing-down efforts'],a:3,
    e:`In a prolonged active second stage despite full dilatation, maternal bearing-down efforts are the principal contributor to fetal expulsion, supplementing uterine contractions to overcome perineal and pelvic floor resistance.<br><br>Total time to delivery should not exceed 4 hours from full dilatation, and active second stage in primigravidae should not exceed 2 hours, beyond which morbidity rises and instrumental delivery is often considered.<br><br>A (retraction alone) is insufficient without expulsive force. B (placental contraction) is not real. C (cervical dilation) is complete by second stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A placenta is delivered with the fetal surface appearing first and minimal external bleeding until expulsion. Which mechanism of separation occurred?',o:['Matthews Duncan','Schultze','Couvelaire','Brandt'],a:1,
    e:`Delivery of the placenta with the fetal (shiny) surface presenting first and minimal external bleeding until expulsion describes the Schultze mechanism, the most common pattern of placental separation.<br><br>Separation begins centrally with formation of a retroplacental haematoma that is contained behind the placenta. Bleeding is concealed until after the placenta is delivered. Matthews Duncan, by contrast, separates from the margin first.<br><br>A (Matthews Duncan) presents maternal surface first with early bleeding. C (Couvelaire) is uterine apoplexy. D (Brandt) refers to a manoeuvre, not a separation pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour progression, uterine contractions increase in intensity. Which physiological change facilitates this?',o:['Reduced calcium influx','Decreased prostaglandin synthesis','Increased oxytocin receptor density','Reduced estrogen levels'],a:2,
    e:`Increasing oxytocin receptor density in the myometrium near term is a key physiological change that allows contractions to grow stronger and more coordinated as labour progresses.<br><br>Receptor up-regulation is driven by rising oestrogen and falling effective progesterone activity. Together with prostaglandin-induced gap junction formation, this produces a myometrium responsive to even small amounts of oxytocin.<br><br>A (reduced calcium influx) opposes contractions. B (decreased prostaglandins) opposes labour. D (reduced oestrogen) is the opposite of what occurs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal head rotates from the transverse to the anteroposterior diameter of the pelvis during labour. This movement is called:',o:['Internal rotation','Flexion','Engagement','Restitution'],a:0,
    e:`Internal rotation is the cardinal movement that turns the fetal head from the transverse position at the inlet to the anteroposterior diameter at the outlet, where AP is the widest diameter.<br><br>The pelvic floor muscles guide the leading occiput anteriorly. A flexed occipito-anterior fetus rotates through one-eighth of a circle; a persistent OP position may rotate through three-eighths to reach OA, prolonging labour.<br><br>B (flexion) reduces head diameter. C (engagement) is the inlet event. D (restitution) follows head delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'As the fetal head passes under the pubic symphysis and the occiput emerges, which cardinal movement occurs?',o:['Flexion','Extension','Descent','Restitution'],a:1,
    e:`Extension is the cardinal movement during which the fetal head emerges from beneath the pubic symphysis. The occiput acts as a fulcrum and the bregma, face and chin appear in succession over the perineum.<br><br>Extension follows internal rotation. Controlled extension reduces perineal trauma; the hands-on approach uses the accoucheur\'s hands to flex the head and guard the perineum as crowning occurs.<br><br>A (flexion) reduces diameter before descent. C (descent) is continuous. D (restitution) realigns head with shoulders after delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'After delivery of the head, it rotates to realign with the fetal shoulders. This movement is known as:',o:['Descent','Flexion','Restitution','Engagement'],a:2,
    e:`Restitution is the cardinal movement immediately following delivery of the head, during which the head rotates through one-eighth of a circle to realign with the shoulders still inside the birth canal.<br><br>It is followed by external rotation, in which the shoulders rotate to the AP plane (widest at the outlet) and the head rotates a further one-eighth, allowing the anterior shoulder to deliver under the pubic symphysis.<br><br>A (descent) is continuous. B (flexion) precedes head delivery. D (engagement) is at the inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida in labour shows arrest of cervical dilation at 8 cm despite strong contractions. Which condition is most likely responsible?',o:['Cephalopelvic disproportion','Premature rupture of membranes','Maternal dehydration','Cervical edema'],a:0,
    e:`Arrest of cervical dilatation at 8 cm despite strong contractions, classified as secondary arrest, is most often caused by cephalopelvic disproportion or fetal malposition or malpresentation.<br><br>Although inefficient uterine contractions can cause primary arrest in the early active phase, secondary arrest typically reflects mechanical obstruction. An obstetrician should assess and oxytocin augmentation must be used cautiously.<br><br>B (premature membrane rupture) does not directly arrest dilatation. C (dehydration) impairs contractility but is not the typical secondary arrest cause. D (cervical oedema) follows pushing too early.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The hydrostatic wedge that assists cervical dilation during labour is formed primarily by:',o:['Umbilical cord','Fetal shoulders','Placenta','Amniotic sac'],a:3,
    e:`The intact bag of forewaters formed by the amniotic sac and amniotic fluid acts as a hydrostatic wedge. It transmits intrauterine pressure evenly to the cervix during contractions and aids effacement and dilatation.<br><br>Once membranes rupture, the well-applied fetal head replaces the wedge. Premature rupture before adequate cervical change can leave a poorly applied head and cause inefficient progress.<br><br>A (umbilical cord) does not form a wedge. B (fetal shoulders) are too large to act as a wedge. C (placenta) sits on the uterine wall.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A labouring woman develops uterine contractions occurring every minute with little relaxation between them. This abnormal pattern is termed:',o:['Hypotonic uterine dysfunction','Secondary uterine inertia','Uterine tachysystole','Precipitous labour'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine tachysystole describes excessively frequent contractions, more than five in 10 minutes, often with little or no relaxation between them. The pattern reduces uteroplacental perfusion and may compromise the fetus.<br><br>Tachysystole is most commonly caused by oxytocin overuse or excessive prostaglandin agents during induction. Continuous electronic fetal monitoring is required, and the offending agent is reduced or stopped if abnormalities arise.<br><br>A (hypotonic dysfunction) is the opposite, with weak contractions. B (secondary inertia) means contractions weaken. D (precipitous labour) is rapid total progress, not contraction frequency alone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the second stage of labour, the fetal head becomes permanently visible without receding between contractions. This sign is called:',o:['Engagement','Crowning','Caput formation','Descent'],a:1,
    e:`Crowning is the moment when the fetal head no longer recedes between contractions and is permanently visible at the introitus. It indicates the head has passed through the pelvic floor and delivery is imminent.<br><br>Once crowning occurs, the woman should be discouraged from active pushing and asked to take rapid shallow breaths (panting) so that the head is delivered slowly. Controlled extension limits perineal trauma.<br><br>A (engagement) is at the pelvic inlet. C (caput formation) is scalp oedema. D (descent) is general progress, not the no-longer-receding sign.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During uterine contraction, uteroplacental blood flow temporarily decreases. Which fetal adaptation helps tolerate this?',o:['High oxygen affinity of fetal hemoglobin','Increased hemoglobin concentration','Reduced fetal metabolism','Increased fetal heart rate variability'],a:0,
    e:`Fetal haemoglobin (HbF) has a higher oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin (HbA), so it loads oxygen at the relatively low oxygen tensions of the placental intervillous space and tolerates the brief reductions during contractions.<br><br>The Bohr effect amplifies this: as fetal blood gives up CO2 in the placenta, its oxygen affinity rises, while the maternal blood\'s falls. Fetal cardiovascular reserve and shunting (ductus venosus, foramen ovale, ductus arteriosus) further protect vital organs.<br><br>B (high Hb concentration) helps but is not the primary contraction-tolerance mechanism. C (reduced fetal metabolism) is incorrect. D (raised heart rate variability) is a sign, not a tolerance mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A placenta separates beginning at the margin with early bleeding before expulsion. Which mechanism occurred?',o:['Schultze','Brandt','Couvelaire','Matthews Duncan'],a:3,
    e:`Placental separation beginning at the margin with early external bleeding before expulsion describes the Matthews Duncan mechanism. The maternal (rough) surface presents first at the introitus.<br><br>Matthews Duncan is the less common pattern (about 20 percent) and is more often associated with retained membranes and incomplete separation. The more common Schultze mechanism separates centrally with concealed bleeding.<br><br>A (Schultze) gives concealed bleeding and fetal surface first. B (Brandt) is a manoeuvre. C (Couvelaire) is uterine apoplexy in severe abruption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida begins pushing before full cervical dilation. Which complication is most likely?',o:['Uterine rupture','Placental abruption','Cervical edema','Shoulder dystocia'],a:2,
    e:`Pushing before full cervical dilatation predisposes to cervical oedema, in which a partly dilated cervix becomes thickened and unable to dilate further, prolonging labour and increasing the risk of operative delivery.<br><br>Active pushing should begin only after full dilatation is confirmed, ideally guided by a spontaneous urge through the Ferguson reflex. Passive descent for 1 to 2 hours is recommended in women with epidural analgesia.<br><br>A (uterine rupture) is more associated with obstructed labour and uterine scars. B (placental abruption) is a separate condition. D (shoulder dystocia) is unrelated to early pushing.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the second stage of labour, pelvic floor muscles guide the fetal head anteriorly. Which cardinal movement is facilitated by this?',o:['Engagement','Flexion','Descent','Internal rotation'],a:3,
    e:`The pelvic floor muscles guide the fetal head anteriorly during the second stage by means of the gutter-shaped levator sling. This is the cardinal movement of internal rotation.<br><br>If the head is well flexed, the leading occiput meets the sloping levator gutter and is encouraged to rotate so that the sagittal suture lies in the AP diameter of the pelvic outlet. Persistent OP may need a long internal rotation.<br><br>A (engagement) is at the inlet. B (flexion) reduces diameter, not rotation. C (descent) is continuous and overlaps multiple movements.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus enters the pelvic inlet with its sagittal suture in the transverse diameter. This indicates:',o:['Flexion','Engagement','Extension','Restitution'],a:1,
    e:`A fetus entering the pelvic inlet with its sagittal suture in the transverse diameter has engaged. The transverse diameter is the widest at the inlet (13.5 cm), so the head naturally takes this orientation.<br><br>Engagement, the first cardinal movement, requires the widest part of the presenting part to pass through the inlet. Internal rotation later brings the sagittal suture to the AP diameter at the outlet, where AP becomes widest.<br><br>A (flexion) reduces head diameter. C (extension) is a delivery movement. D (restitution) follows head delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Multiparous women typically experience shorter second stage of labour due to:',o:['Reduced pelvic resistance and effective expulsive efforts','Smaller fetus','Increased progesterone levels','Reduced uterine contractions'],a:0,
    e:`Multiparous women experience shorter second stages mainly because reduced perineal and pelvic floor resistance combined with effective expulsive efforts allow more rapid descent and delivery.<br><br>Active second stage should normally last no more than 1 hour in a multipara compared with 2 hours in a primigravida. The cervix is also already partly effaced, and an already-stretched birth canal offers less resistance.<br><br>B (smaller fetus) is not consistently true. C (raised progesterone) is unrelated. D (reduced contractions) is not characteristic of multiparous labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, intermittent fetal hypoxia occurs during contractions. Which fetal characteristic provides protection?',o:['Reduced placental circulation','Increased fetal hemoglobin oxygen affinity','Increased fetal metabolism','Umbilical vasoconstriction'],a:1,
    e:`Fetal haemoglobin\'s higher oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin allows the fetus to tolerate the intermittent hypoxia of contractions, when uteroplacental blood flow temporarily falls.<br><br>HbF\'s left-shifted oxygen dissociation curve loads oxygen efficiently at the low oxygen tensions of the placental intervillous space. The Bohr effect amplifies this: maternal blood gives up oxygen as it acidifies, while fetal blood loads it.<br><br>A (reduced placental circulation) worsens hypoxia. C (raised metabolism) increases demand. D (umbilical vasoconstriction) reduces oxygen delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida with strong uterine contractions shows no cervical change. Which dysfunction is most likely?',o:['Placental separation','Cervical ripening','Failure of uterine polarity','Membrane rupture'],a:2,
    e:`Strong uterine contractions producing no cervical change suggest failure of polarity: the upper segment is contracting but the lower segment and cervix are not appropriately relaxing and stretching, so the directional force is dissipated.<br><br>True dysfunctional labour with intact polarity tends to show weak or infrequent contractions. Loss of polarity raises concern for malposition, malpresentation or cephalopelvic disproportion. An obstetrician must reassess.<br><br>A (placental separation) is third stage. B (cervical ripening) is the desired prelabour change. D (membrane rupture) is independent.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The cervix becomes thin and blends with the lower uterine segment during labour. This process is known as:',o:['Flexion','Engagement','Descent','Effacement'],a:3,
    e:`Effacement is the process by which the cervix becomes thin and blends with the lower uterine segment. By the end, the cervix is fully thinned and continuous with the lower segment.<br><br>Driven by retraction of upper segment fibres, effacement is usually complete before significant dilatation in primigravidae but proceeds simultaneously with dilatation in multiparous women. The 36-week cervix is approximately 3 cm long.<br><br>A (flexion) is a fetal head movement. B (engagement) is descent of the head. C (descent) is general progress through the pelvis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The occiput rotates anteriorly to lie beneath the pubic symphysis before delivery. Which movement is responsible?',o:['Internal rotation','Flexion','Extension','Restitution'],a:0,
    e:`Anterior rotation of the occiput to lie beneath the pubic symphysis before delivery is achieved by internal rotation, the cardinal movement guided by the gutter-shaped levator sling.<br><br>A flexed occipito-anterior fetus rotates through one-eighth of a circle; a persistent occipito-posterior position may rotate through three-eighths (long arc) and prolong labour. The result is the sagittal suture in the AP diameter at the outlet.<br><br>B (flexion) reduces head diameter. C (extension) is a delivery movement. D (restitution) follows head delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'In the third stage of labour, the uterus becomes firm and rises in the abdomen. What does this signify?',o:['Uterine rupture','Cervical contraction','Vaginal dilation','Placental separation'],a:3,
    e:`In the third stage, a uterus that becomes firm and globular and rises in the abdomen signifies placental separation. The placenta has detached from the decidua basalis and descended into the lower segment.<br><br>Other supporting signs are cord lengthening at the introitus and a small gush of blood. Confirmation of separation precedes safe controlled cord traction; pulling on the cord before separation risks uterine inversion.<br><br>A (rupture) presents with collapse and severe pain. B (cervical contraction) is unrelated to fundus appearance. C (vaginal dilation) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus delivers its head but shoulders fail to rotate externally. Which movement has failed?',o:['External rotation','Restitution','Flexion','Engagement'],a:0,
    e:`Failure of the shoulders to rotate after delivery of the head represents failure of external rotation. Without rotation to the AP plane, the anterior shoulder cannot deliver under the pubic symphysis.<br><br>External rotation follows restitution. The wider AP diameter at the outlet must accommodate the bisacromial diameter. Persistent failure of shoulder rotation can lead to shoulder dystocia, an obstetric emergency requiring specific manoeuvres.<br><br>B (restitution) realigns the head with shoulders, not shoulder rotation itself. C (flexion) reduces head diameter. D (engagement) is at the inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, myometrial cells communicate through gap junctions. The primary advantage of this is:',o:['Increased placental blood flow','Coordinated uterine contractions','Reduced uterine tone','Cervical stiffening'],a:1,
    e:`The primary advantage of gap junctions between myometrial cells is coordinated propagation of action potentials, allowing the entire upper segment to contract synchronously and generate effective expulsive force.<br><br>Gap junctions are scarce in early pregnancy and form in significant numbers at term under prostaglandin influence. Their formation is a key part of the transition from a relaxed quiescent uterus to an actively contracting one.<br><br>A (raise placental flow) is unrelated. C (reduce uterine tone) is the opposite of their effect. D (cervical stiffening) is opposite to ripening.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida has second stage lasting 3 hours despite adequate contractions. Which physiological factor may contribute?',o:['Uterine rupture','Placental separation','Pelvic floor resistance','Cervical ripening'],a:2,
    e:`A second stage exceeding 2 hours despite adequate contractions in a primigravida often reflects pelvic floor resistance. The perineum is taut and relatively resistant in nulliparous women, prolonging the descent and delivery phase.<br><br>Beyond 3 hours, both maternal and fetal morbidity rise and instrumental delivery is often considered. Women with epidural analgesia frequently require longer second stages because the bearing-down urge is blunted.<br><br>A (uterine rupture) is an acute emergency. B (placental separation) belongs to third stage. D (cervical ripening) is a pre-labour event.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During delivery, the fetal head extends around the pubic symphysis. Which structure acts as the pivot point?',o:['Sacral promontory','Pubic symphysis','Ischial spine','Coccyx'],a:1,
    e:`During delivery, the fetal head extends around the pubic symphysis. The undersurface of the symphysis acts as the pivot point as the occiput escapes from beneath it and the bregma, face and chin sweep over the perineum.<br><br>Extension is the cardinal movement immediately preceding delivery of the head. Controlled extension limits perineal trauma; the hands-on technique uses the accoucheur\'s hands to flex the head and guard the perineum.<br><br>A (sacral promontory) is the inlet posterior border. C (ischial spine) is the midpelvis landmark. D (coccyx) is too inferior to act as the pivot.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Descent and rotation of the fetal head during labour are mainly driven by:',o:['Uterine contractions guided by pelvic floor','Pelvic ligament contraction','Placental pressure','Fetal breathing movements'],a:0,
    e:`Descent and rotation of the fetal head during labour are driven by uterine contractions, with rotation guided by the gutter-shaped levator sling of the pelvic floor as the head descends through the midpelvis.<br><br>In the active second stage, maternal voluntary bearing-down efforts add to the expulsive force. The bony pelvic shape, the levator gutter and a flexed occipito-anterior fetus together optimise the mechanism of labour.<br><br>B (pelvic ligament contraction) is incorrect; ligaments soften and stretch. C (placental pressure) does not propel the fetus. D (fetal breathing) does not propel.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Uterine contractions increase in strength during labour due to rising intracellular levels of:',o:['Sodium','Potassium','Calcium','Chloride'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine contraction strength rises with increasing intracellular free calcium, which binds calmodulin to activate myosin light-chain kinase, allowing actin-myosin filaments to interact and shorten the cell.<br><br>Prostaglandins and oxytocin both increase intracellular calcium influx, while beta-adrenergic agonists and calcium channel blockers oppose it. This is the basis for the use of nifedipine and salbutamol as tocolytics.<br><br>A (sodium) does not directly trigger smooth muscle contraction. B (potassium) increase causes hyperpolarisation and relaxation. D (chloride) is not the contraction trigger.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A pathological retraction ring appears during labour. This is usually a sign of:',o:['Normal labour','Uterine relaxation','Placental separation','Obstructed labour'],a:3,
    e:`A pathological retraction ring (Bandl ring) appearing during labour is a sign of obstructed labour. It develops at the junction of the thick upper segment and the thinned lower segment as obstruction continues.<br><br>The ring rises progressively as obstruction worsens, signals impending uterine rupture, and is an indication for urgent delivery, usually by caesarean section. It is most often seen in neglected obstructed labour.<br><br>A (normal labour) is incorrect; Bandl ring is always pathological. B (relaxation) is the opposite of retraction. C (placental separation) is third stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Retraction of uterine muscle fibers during labour mainly ensures:',o:['Progressive fetal descent without reversal','Cervical closure','Increased placental blood flow','Reduced uterine contractions'],a:0,
    e:`Retraction ensures progressive descent without reversal. Each contraction shortens upper-segment fibres permanently so the fetus does not slip back when the contraction ends, producing cumulative gain across successive contractions.<br><br>Retraction also builds the thicker upper segment that generates expulsive force. After delivery, sustained retraction compresses placental bed vessels and prevents postpartum haemorrhage; failure of retraction causes uterine atony.<br><br>B (cervical closure) is unrelated to retraction. C (raise placental flow) is the opposite of contraction effects. D (reduce contractions) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Cervical softening before labour occurs mainly due to:',o:['Increased collagen cross-linking','Collagen breakdown mediated by prostaglandins','Reduced cervical vascularity','Increased progesterone'],a:1,
    e:`Cervical softening before labour occurs mainly through prostaglandin-mediated proteolysis: increased proteolytic activity reduces collagen and elastin, and dermatan sulphate is replaced by hydrophilic hyaluronic acid.<br><br>These changes raise water content and produce ripening. Interleukins drive a proinflammatory shift with neutrophil invasion. PGE2 (dinoprostone) is used clinically to mimic this process for induction of labour.<br><br>A (collagen cross-linking) opposes ripening. C (reduced vascularity) is incorrect; vascularity rises. D (raised progesterone) maintains relaxation, not softening.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'After delivery of the baby, placenta fails to separate despite contractions. Which physiological mechanism has failed?',o:['Pelvic floor relaxation','Cervical dilatation','Internal rotation','Uterine retraction'],a:3,
    e:`Failure of the placenta to separate after delivery despite contractions reflects inadequate uterine retraction. Without adequate retraction, the cleavage plane in the decidua basalis does not develop, and the placenta does not detach.<br><br>Risk factors include prolonged or augmented labour, multiple pregnancy, polyhydramnios and precipitous delivery. Active management with oxytocin reinforces retraction and reduces both retention and postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (pelvic floor relaxation) is unrelated. B (cervical dilatation) is first stage. C (internal rotation) is a fetal movement, not placental separation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, fetal hemoglobin assists oxygen transfer because it:',o:['Has lower oxygen affinity','Rapidly converts to adult hemoglobin','Has higher oxygen affinity','Does not bind carbon dioxide'],a:2,
    e:`Fetal haemoglobin (HbF) has a higher oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin, allowing it to load oxygen at the low oxygen tensions of the placental intervillous space and ensure adequate fetal oxygenation.<br><br>HbF\'s oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve is left-shifted relative to HbA. The Bohr effect amplifies this: maternal blood acidifies and gives up oxygen, while fetal blood alkalinises and loads it. HbF dominates until late gestation.<br><br>A (lower affinity) is incorrect. B (rapid conversion) is incorrect; HbF persists for weeks postnatally. D (does not bind CO2) is incorrect; HbF binds CO2 normally.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Normal fetal development and growth)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman receiving epidural analgesia develops prolonged second stage of labour. Which physiological factor is reduced?',o:['Uterine contractions','Maternal bearing-down reflex','Cervical ripening','Placental blood flow'],a:1,
    e:`Epidural analgesia reduces the maternal bearing-down reflex by blunting afferent transmission of pelvic floor and vaginal stretch. Without the urge, voluntary pushing must be guided, prolonging the active second stage.<br><br>A passive second stage of 1 to 2 hours is usually allowed with an epidural to permit descent and rotation before active pushing. Total time to delivery should not exceed 4 hours from full dilatation.<br><br>A (uterine contractions) are not directly reduced by epidural. C (cervical ripening) is unrelated. D (placental blood flow) is not the relevant factor.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Moulding of the fetal skull during labour occurs due to:',o:['Overlapping cranial sutures','Fusion of cranial bones','Thickening of skull bones','Expansion of cranial bones'],a:0,
    e:`Moulding of the fetal skull occurs because the cranial sutures are unossified at term, allowing the bony plates to overlap. The parietal bones typically slide over the frontal and occipital bones.<br><br>Bones themselves are also compressible, so moulding reduces the diameters of the fetal head while still protecting the underlying brain. Severe or early moulding can be a sign of obstructed labour or cephalopelvic disproportion.<br><br>B (fusion of cranial bones) is incorrect; sutures are not yet fused. C (thickening of bones) does not occur. D (expansion) is the opposite of moulding.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, the upper uterine segment becomes thicker while the lower segment thins. This helps:',o:['Initiate placental separation','Prevent uterine contractions','Promote fetal descent','Prevent cervical dilation'],a:2,
    e:`The thicker actively contracting upper segment and the thinner distensible lower segment together produce uterine polarity, generating the directional force that drives fetal descent through the birth canal.<br><br>Retraction of upper-segment fibres builds the upper segment and effaces the cervix; passive stretching of the lower segment accommodates the descending fetus. Loss of polarity produces dysfunctional labour and arrest of progress.<br><br>A (placental separation) is third stage. B (prevent contractions) is incorrect. D (prevent dilation) is opposite to actual effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'After placental delivery, sustained uterine contraction primarily prevents postpartum hemorrhage by:',o:['Closing the cervix','Expelling retained membranes','Increasing maternal blood pressure','Compressing uterine blood vessels'],a:3,
    e:`After placental delivery, sustained uterine contraction prevents postpartum haemorrhage primarily by compressing the spiral arteries running through the lattice-arranged myometrial fibres of the upper segment.<br><br>This living-ligature mechanism is the principal initial haemostatic force, far more important than coagulation. Failure of contraction (atony) leaves vessels open and is the leading cause of postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (closing the cervix) is irrelevant to placental bed bleeding. B (expelling membranes) is a separate process. C (raising blood pressure) is incidental.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A 24-year-old primigravida at term is in labour with cervical dilatation of 9 cm and strong contractions every 2 minutes. She suddenly develops an intense urge to push. What is the most appropriate explanation for this physiological event?',o:['Stretching of cervix and vagina triggering oxytocin release','Sudden placental separation','Increased progesterone secretion','Decreased uterine blood flow'],a:0,
    e:`Strong contractions with the cervix at 9 cm and an intense urge to push are explained by the Ferguson reflex: stretching of the cervix and upper vagina by the descending presenting part triggers oxytocin release from the posterior pituitary.<br><br>The reflex amplifies labour as it advances and contributes to the bearing-down urge. The active second stage typically begins when the maternal urge to push prompts re-examination, often coinciding with full dilatation.<br><br>B (placental separation) is third stage. C (raised progesterone) opposes labour. D (reduced uterine flow) is a contraction effect, not the urge trigger.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the second stage of labour, the fetal head descends and rotates so that the occiput lies beneath the pubic symphysis. Which anatomical structure primarily guides this rotation?',o:['Sacral promontory','Uterine fundus','Pelvic floor muscles','Amniotic sac'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic floor muscles, formed by the levator ani and their fascia, create a gutter-shaped musculofascial sling that guides the fetal head to flex and rotate anteriorly during the second stage.<br><br>If the head is well flexed, the leading occiput meets the sloping gutter and is encouraged to rotate so the sagittal suture lies in the AP diameter of the pelvic outlet. This brings the occiput beneath the pubic symphysis.<br><br>A (sacral promontory) is part of the bony inlet. B (uterine fundus) generates contractions but does not guide rotation. D (amniotic sac) acts as a hydrostatic wedge before rupture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida has been in labour for several hours. Despite adequate contractions, the fetal head fails to descend and the sagittal suture remains in the transverse diameter at the level of the ischial spines. Which physiological step has not yet occurred?',o:['Flexion','Engagement','Extension','Internal rotation'],a:3,
    e:`Failure of descent with the sagittal suture in the transverse diameter at the ischial spines indicates that internal rotation has not occurred. The head should rotate so the suture lies in the AP outlet diameter.<br><br>Internal rotation is guided by the levator sling and depends on adequate flexion. Persistent transverse arrest at the spines (deep transverse arrest) is associated with android pelves and may need rotational instrumental delivery.<br><br>A (flexion) reduces head diameter, which has likely already happened. B (engagement) precedes ischial-spine descent. C (extension) is a delivery movement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman delivers the baby, and within a few minutes there is a sudden gush of blood with lengthening of the umbilical cord. The uterus becomes firm and rises in the abdomen. Which physiological mechanism explains this finding?',o:['Cervical closure','Separation of placenta from uterine wall','Vaginal muscle contraction','Rupture of fetal membranes'],a:1,
    e:`A sudden gush of blood with cord lengthening and a firm globular uterus rising in the abdomen are the classic signs of placental separation from the uterine wall.<br><br>These signs allow safe controlled cord traction. Pulling on the cord before separation risks uterine inversion, particularly if the suprapubic hand does not adequately support the uterus during traction.<br><br>A (cervical closure) is unrelated. C (vaginal contraction) does not produce these signs. D (rupture of membranes) precedes delivery and gives clear fluid loss, not bloody gush.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During labour, uterine contractions progressively increase in strength and coordination due to formation of numerous gap junctions between myometrial cells. Which physiological advantage does this provide?',o:['Decreased uterine tone','Increased placental perfusion','Inhibition of oxytocin release','Coordinated propagation of uterine contractions'],a:3,
    e:`Numerous gap junctions between myometrial cells allow rapid spread of action potentials and produce coordinated propagation of contractions across the upper segment, building strength and synchrony as labour progresses.<br><br>Gap junctions are scarce in early pregnancy but form in significant numbers at term under prostaglandin influence. They turn the upper segment into a functional syncytium that contracts as a single unit.<br><br>A (decreased tone) is opposite. B (raised placental perfusion) is unrelated to gap junctions. C (inhibition of oxytocin) is opposite to physiology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus in vertex presentation descends through the pelvis and the head emerges under the pubic symphysis. The face then sweeps over the perineum. Which cardinal movement is occurring at this moment?',o:['Engagement','Internal rotation','Extension','Descent'],a:2,
    e:`When the head emerges under the pubic symphysis and the face sweeps over the perineum, the cardinal movement occurring is extension. The occiput acts as a fulcrum as the bregma, face and chin appear in succession.<br><br>Extension follows internal rotation. Controlled extension limits perineal trauma; the hands-on technique uses the accoucheur\'s hands to flex the head and guard the perineum as crowning occurs.<br><br>A (engagement) is at the inlet. B (internal rotation) precedes extension. D (descent) is continuous.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'After delivery of the fetal head, the head rotates to one side to align with the shoulders still inside the birth canal. This movement is known as:',o:['Restitution','Engagement','Flexion','Descent'],a:0,
    e:`Restitution is the cardinal movement in which the fetal head, after delivery, rotates through one-eighth of a circle to one side to realign with the shoulders still inside the birth canal.<br><br>Restitution is followed by external rotation, in which the shoulders rotate to the AP plane (widest at the outlet) and the head rotates a further one-eighth, allowing the anterior shoulder to deliver under the pubic symphysis.<br><br>B (engagement) is at the inlet. C (flexion) precedes head delivery. D (descent) is continuous.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida reaches the second stage of labour. During examination, the fetal head is visible at the vulva even when contractions cease. What physiological stage of delivery does this represent?',o:['Engagement','Crowning','Internal rotation','Descent'],a:1,
    e:`The fetal head remaining visible at the vulva even when contractions cease is crowning, the moment when the head has passed through the pelvic floor and delivery is imminent.<br><br>Once crowning occurs, the woman is asked to take rapid shallow breaths (panting) so the head is delivered slowly. The hands-on technique helps control extension and limit perineal trauma.<br><br>A (engagement) is at the inlet, not the vulva. C (internal rotation) precedes crowning. D (descent) is general progress, not the no-longer-receding sign.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'During the third stage of labour, uterine muscle fibers shorten permanently and compress blood vessels supplying the placental bed. What is this physiological mechanism called?',o:['Retraction','Dilatation','Relaxation','Effacement'],a:0,
    e:`Permanent shortening of uterine muscle fibres after each contraction, with subsequent compression of placental bed vessels, is called retraction. It is the unique property that distinguishes uterine smooth muscle.<br><br>Actin-myosin interactions occur along the full filament length, leaving fibres progressively shortened. This builds the upper segment that generates expulsive force and, after delivery, produces living-ligature haemostasis.<br><br>B (dilatation) is opening of the cervix. C (relaxation) returns muscle to original length. D (effacement) is shortening of the cervix, not myometrium.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A labouring woman has effective uterine contractions but poor progress of cervical dilation. Investigation shows inadequate cervical softening due to reduced prostaglandin activity. Which physiological process is primarily impaired?',o:['Uterine polarity','Cervical ripening','Fetal descent','Placental separation'],a:1,
    e:`Effective contractions with poor cervical dilatation due to inadequate cervical softening from reduced prostaglandin activity is impairment of cervical ripening, the prelabour change that prepares the cervix for effacement and dilatation.<br><br>Ripening involves prostaglandin-mediated proteolysis, replacement of dermatan sulphate by hyaluronic acid, and increased water content. Without ripening, even strong contractions cannot dilate a firm closed cervix efficiently.<br><br>A (uterine polarity) is intact if contractions are effective. C (fetal descent) follows dilatation. D (placental separation) is third stage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A 26-year-old woman on the third postpartum day notices reduction in uterine size and firmness on abdominal examination. Which physiological process is primarily responsible for this change?',o:['Pelvic ligament contraction','Cervical dilatation','Increased placental hormones','Uterine involution due to autolysis of myometrial fibers'],a:3,
    e:`Reduction in uterine size during puerperium is achieved by involution: muscle cells diminish in size as a result of enzymatic digestion of cytoplasm, an autolytic process that does not change cell number.<br><br>The protein released by autolysis is absorbed into the bloodstream and excreted in the urine. Involution is accelerated by oxytocin release in breastfeeding women, so the uterus is smaller than in those who bottle-feed.<br><br>A (pelvic ligament contraction) does not reduce uterine size. B (cervical dilatation) is a labour event. C (raised placental hormones) opposes involution.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Immediately after delivery, the uterine fundus is normally palpable at which anatomical level?',o:['Midway between symphysis pubis and umbilicus','Two fingerbreadths above the umbilicus','At the level of the umbilicus','At the level of the xiphisternum'],a:2,
    e:`Immediately after delivery the uterine fundus is normally palpable at approximately the level of the umbilicus, lying about 4 cm below the umbilicus or roughly 12 cm above the symphysis pubis.<br><br>By 2 weeks the uterus is no longer palpable above the symphysis pubis. The fundus typically descends by about 1 cm per day. The uterus is larger after caesarean section and in multiparous women.<br><br>A (midway between symphysis and umbilicus) is too low. B (two fingerbreadths above) is rare and worrying. D (xiphisternum) is far too high.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman on the fifth postpartum day has vaginal discharge that is pinkish-brown. What type of lochia is this?',o:['Lochia rubra','Lochia purulenta','Lochia alba','Lochia serosa'],a:3,
    e:`Pinkish-brown vaginal discharge on the fifth postpartum day is lochia serosa, the second phase of lochia. It contains serous fluid, leukocytes, cervical mucus and small amounts of blood from regenerating endometrium.<br><br>Lochia rubra (red, blood and decidual debris) lasts about 1 to 3 days. Lochia serosa appears around days 4 to 10. Lochia alba (yellow-white) follows from about day 10 and may persist for several weeks.<br><br>A (lochia rubra) is fresh red blood within the first few days. B (lochia purulenta) is not a normal type. C (lochia alba) is yellow-white and appears later.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During the puerperium, the uterus gradually returns to its nonpregnant size. Approximately how long does complete uterine involution usually take?',o:['1 week','2 weeks','6 weeks','12 weeks'],a:2,
    e:`The puerperium covers the 6-week period after delivery, during which uterine involution and other physiological adjustments return the body to the pre-pregnant state. Complete involution typically takes around 6 weeks.<br><br>The placental implantation site usually heals completely by about 6 weeks. The formal postnatal examination is performed at this point, assessing the woman\'s mental and physical recovery, urinary, bowel and sexual function.<br><br>A (1 week) is when the uterus reaches a 14-week-sized state. B (2 weeks) is when the uterus becomes a pelvic organ again. D (12 weeks) is well beyond complete involution.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman begins breastfeeding within one hour of delivery. Which hormone is primarily responsible for milk ejection during suckling?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Estrogen'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin is the hormone of milk ejection during suckling. Suckling stimulates pulsatile release from the maternal posterior pituitary, contracting myoepithelial cells around the alveoli and lactiferous ducts.<br><br>The let-down reflex can also be triggered by visual, olfactory or auditory stimuli such as hearing the baby cry, but is inhibited by stress. Oxytocin also stimulates uterine contraction, producing after-pains during early breastfeeding.<br><br>A (prolactin) drives milk synthesis but not ejection. C (progesterone) inhibits lactation antenatally. D (oestrogen) is not the let-down hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'On the first postpartum day, the uterus is firm and located one fingerbreadth below the umbilicus. This finding indicates:',o:['Normal involution','Uterine atony','Retained placenta','Subinvolution'],a:0,
    e:`On the first postpartum day, a firm uterus one fingerbreadth below the umbilicus represents normal involution. The fundus descends from the level of the umbilicus by about 1 cm per day during the puerperium.<br><br>Persistent fundal height or a soft boggy uterus suggests subinvolution or atony, often associated with retained products of conception or uterine infection. Bladder distension can also displace the uterus and falsely raise fundal height.<br><br>B (atony) presents with a boggy uterus and bleeding. C (retained placenta) is a third stage event. D (subinvolution) shows persistent enlargement, not the normal pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the endometrial lining regenerates after placental separation. Which layer primarily regenerates the endometrium?',o:['Decidua basalis','Decidua capsularis','Chorionic villi','Basal layer of endometrium'],a:3,
    e:`After placental separation only the superficial layer of the decidua becomes necrotic and is sloughed off. The basal layer adjacent to the myometrium regenerates new endometrium, complete by the third week.<br><br>Persistent red lochia beyond the normal timeframe suggests delayed involution, usually associated with infection or retained placental tissue, and may present as secondary postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (decidua basalis) is the maternal placental contribution and is sloughed. B (decidua capsularis) covers the gestational sac and is also lost. C (chorionic villi) are fetal structures.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The initial postpartum vaginal discharge composed mainly of blood and decidual debris is called:',o:['Lochia alba','Lochia serosa','Lochia rubra','Lochia mucosa'],a:2,
    e:`Lochia rubra is the initial red lochia of the first few days postpartum, composed mainly of blood and necrotic decidual debris from the superficial decidua sloughed after placental separation.<br><br>It changes over time: pink-brown lochia serosa around days 4 to 10, then yellow-white lochia alba from around day 10, lasting up to a month. Persistent rubra suggests delayed involution from infection or retained tissue.<br><br>A (lochia alba) is the late yellow-white discharge. B (lochia serosa) is the intermediate pink-brown phase. D (lochia mucosa) is not a recognised classification.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A breastfeeding mother experiences uterine cramps during nursing in the early puerperium. This is primarily due to release of:',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:0,
    e:`Uterine cramps during breastfeeding (after-pains) result from oxytocin release triggered by suckling. Oxytocin stimulates myometrial contraction in addition to its action on breast myoepithelial cells for milk ejection.<br><br>After-pains are more pronounced in multiparous women and may require simple analgesia. The same oxytocin-driven contraction accelerates uterine involution, which is why breastfeeding mothers have smaller uteri than bottle-feeders.<br><br>B (oestrogen) does not stimulate uterine contractions during breastfeeding. C (prolactin) drives milk synthesis only. D (progesterone) is low postpartum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman complains of excessive lochia lasting beyond two weeks. Which physiological abnormality is most likely responsible?',o:['Cervical incompetence','Uterine subinvolution','Placental calcification','Increased prolactin'],a:1,
    e:`Excessive lochia lasting beyond 2 weeks suggests uterine subinvolution, the failure of normal involution. This is typically caused by retained products of conception or endometrial infection (endometritis).<br><br>Persistent red lochia, an enlarged tender uterus and an open internal cervical os support the diagnosis. Treatment may require uterine evacuation and antibiotics. Heavy bleeding warrants oxytocics and circulatory support.<br><br>A (cervical incompetence) is a pregnancy condition. C (placental calcification) is not a postpartum lochia cause. D (raised prolactin) does not cause prolonged lochia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The cervix after delivery gradually regains tone but usually remains slightly open. Which characteristic is typical of a parous cervix?',o:['Slit-shaped external os','Circular external os','Completely closed os','Funnel-shaped os'],a:0,
    e:`After delivery the cervix gradually regains tone but the external os usually remains permanently open in a slit-shaped configuration, characteristic of a parous cervix and distinguishing it from the circular nulliparous os.<br><br>In the first few days the cervix admits two fingers; by the end of the first week it admits one. The internal os is closed by the end of the second week, though the external os keeps its parous funnel shape.<br><br>B (circular os) is the nulliparous appearance. C (completely closed) does not occur permanently in parous women. D (funnel-shaped) is not the typical post-delivery appearance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological process contributes most to reduction in uterine size during puerperium?',o:['Hyperplasia of muscle fibers','Cervical shortening','Increased placental hormones','Autolysis of myometrial cells'],a:3,
    e:`Reduction in uterine size during puerperium is mainly the result of autolysis of myometrial cells. Enzymatic digestion of cytoplasm shrinks each cell without altering cell number, releasing protein into the bloodstream.<br><br>The released protein is excreted in the urine. The process is accelerated by oxytocin release during breastfeeding, which is why breastfeeding mothers have smaller uteri than those who bottle-feed.<br><br>A (hyperplasia) increases cell number, opposite to involution. B (cervical shortening) is unrelated to uterine size. C (raised placental hormones) actually fall postpartum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine fundus typically descends by approximately how much per day during puerperium?',o:['0.5 cm/day','1 cm/day','2 cm/day','3 cm/day'],a:1,
    e:`The uterine fundus descends by approximately 1 cm per day during puerperium. Immediately after delivery the fundus is at the umbilicus; by day 7 at the 14-week sized level; by 2 weeks no longer palpable above the symphysis.<br><br>The descent is more rapid in breastfeeding women due to oxytocin-driven uterine contraction. Persistent or rising fundal height suggests subinvolution, retained products or infection.<br><br>A (0.5 cm/day) is slower than normal. C (2 cm/day) is faster than typical. D (3 cm/day) would be unusually rapid.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman develops milk secretion 3 days after delivery. Which hormonal change triggers lactogenesis?',o:['Decrease in prolactin','Increase in estrogen','Sudden fall in progesterone','Increase in cortisol'],a:2,
    e:`The trigger for stage II lactogenesis is the sudden fall in placental progesterone and oestrogen after placental delivery, which removes their inhibition of prolactin\'s action on the breast.<br><br>Prolactin from the anterior pituitary then drives milk synthesis. Levels of prolactin rise up to 20-fold during pregnancy and lactation, and peak within 45 minutes of suckling. Stage II usually starts 48 to 72 hours postpartum.<br><br>A (decreased prolactin) opposes lactogenesis. B (raised oestrogen) inhibits milk synthesis. D (raised cortisol) supports lactation but is not the trigger.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, thrombosis risk increases due to physiological hypercoagulability. Which factor contributes most?',o:['Reduced fibrinogen levels','Increased fibrinolysis','Reduced platelet aggregation','Increased clotting factors'],a:3,
    e:`Postpartum thrombosis risk rises mainly because pregnancy and the puerperium produce a hypercoagulable state with increased levels of clotting factors including factor VII, VIII, IX, X and fibrinogen.<br><br>Together with venous stasis from reduced mobility and endothelial trauma during delivery, this creates Virchow\'s triad and explains why fatal thromboembolism is most common in the puerperium and after caesarean section.<br><br>A (reduced fibrinogen) is opposite. B (increased fibrinolysis) is opposite. C (reduced platelet aggregation) is opposite.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Lochia alba typically appears around which postpartum period?',o:['After day 10','Days 4-10','Days 1-3','After 6 weeks'],a:0,
    e:`Lochia alba, the third and final phase, appears after about day 10 and may continue for up to a month. It is a scanty yellow-white discharge composed mainly of leukocytes, mucus and serous fluid.<br><br>It follows lochia rubra (red, days 1 to 3) and lochia serosa (pink-brown, days 4 to 10). The succession reflects progressive endometrial regeneration from the basal layer, which is complete by the third week.<br><br>B (days 4 to 10) is lochia serosa. C (days 1 to 3) is lochia rubra. D (after 6 weeks) is beyond normal lochial duration.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman complains of urinary retention after vaginal delivery. Which physiological factor most commonly contributes to this?',o:['Decreased bladder capacity','Increased estrogen levels','Perineal edema and pain','Urethral shortening'],a:2,
    e:`Postpartum urinary retention is most often caused by perineal oedema and pain, particularly after instrumental delivery, episiotomy or extensive lacerations. Periurethral swelling and reflex inhibition impair voiding.<br><br>Other contributors include epidural anaesthesia, which can leave the bladder insensate for up to 8 hours, and high-volume oxytocin infusions during labour. Overdistension can damage the detrusor and cause overflow incontinence.<br><br>A (decreased bladder capacity) is incorrect. B (raised oestrogen) is opposite of postpartum hormones. D (urethral shortening) is not a typical cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, ovarian activity usually resumes earliest in which group?',o:['Breastfeeding mothers','Non-breastfeeding mothers','Women with cesarean delivery','Women with anemia'],a:1,
    e:`Ovarian activity resumes earliest in non-breastfeeding mothers. The first postpartum ovulation in non-lactating women usually occurs around 6 weeks after delivery, sometimes earlier.<br><br>In lactating women, high prolactin levels suppress GnRH pulsatility from the hypothalamus and inhibit ovulation. The lactational amenorrhoea method is reliable only with exclusive breastfeeding for the first 6 months.<br><br>A (breastfeeding mothers) have delayed ovulation. C (caesarean) does not delay ovarian recovery. D (anaemia) does not specifically delay ovulation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The hormone primarily responsible for milk production in the postpartum period is:',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:3,
    e:`Prolactin from the anterior pituitary is the principal hormone driving milk synthesis postpartum. Levels rise up to 20-fold during pregnancy and lactation, and peak within 45 minutes of suckling.<br><br>Nipple stimulation reduces release of prolactin-inhibiting factor (dopamine) from the hypothalamus, allowing prolactin secretion. Lactation can be arrested with bromocryptine, a dopamine agonist that suppresses prolactin.<br><br>A (progesterone) inhibits lactation antenatally. B (oxytocin) drives milk ejection, not synthesis. C (oestrogen) inhibits prolactin\'s effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological event prevents excessive bleeding from placental site during puerperium?',o:['Cervical contraction','Myometrial contraction and retraction','Vaginal muscle contraction','Pelvic ligament shortening'],a:1,
    e:`Sustained myometrial contraction and retraction prevent excessive bleeding from the placental site by compressing the spiral arteries running through the uterine wall. This living-ligature effect is the principal haemostatic mechanism.<br><br>Failure of contraction (uterine atony) is the leading cause of postpartum haemorrhage. Active management with intramuscular oxytocin reinforces this mechanism and reduces PPH from approximately 15 percent to 5 percent.<br><br>A (cervical contraction) does not control placental bed bleeding. C (vaginal contraction) is not haemostatic. D (pelvic ligament shortening) does not occur.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental site typically heals completely by:',o:['6 weeks','2 weeks','1 week','12 weeks'],a:0,
    e:`The placental implantation site is usually completely healed by approximately 6 weeks postpartum. Healing involves regeneration of the endometrium from the basal layer and progressive narrowing and obliteration of the uterine vessels supplying the site.<br><br>The endometrial cavity itself is fully relined by about 3 weeks. Complete healing is one of the milestones reached during the 6-week puerperium and is checked at the formal postnatal examination.<br><br>B (2 weeks) is when the uterus becomes a pelvic organ again. C (1 week) is far too early. D (12 weeks) is beyond standard healing time.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During the puerperium, which hormone level remains elevated in breastfeeding women?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','Relaxin'],a:2,
    e:`In breastfeeding women, prolactin remains elevated postpartum, with levels driven repeatedly upward by suckling. Peaks occur within 45 minutes of suckling and prolactin remains higher than baseline throughout the breastfeeding period.<br><br>High prolactin suppresses GnRH from the hypothalamus, inhibiting ovulation and producing lactational amenorrhoea. In non-breastfeeding women, prolactin returns to normal soon after delivery and ovulation resumes within weeks.<br><br>A (progesterone) falls sharply after placental delivery. B (oestrogen) is low in breastfeeding women. D (relaxin) is no longer secreted.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman complains of excessive sweating during the first few days. What physiological change explains this?',o:['Placental hormone release','Increased estrogen secretion','Reduced metabolism','Fluid mobilization from extracellular space'],a:3,
    e:`Excessive sweating in the first few postpartum days is mainly due to mobilisation of fluid accumulated during pregnancy from the extracellular space, with subsequent loss through diuresis and diaphoresis.<br><br>Pregnancy adds approximately 6 to 8 litres of total body water. Mobilisation begins within hours of delivery and continues over the first postpartum week, contributing to early postpartum weight loss.<br><br>A (placental hormone release) actually falls. B (raised oestrogen) is opposite. C (reduced metabolism) does not cause sweating.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the uterine weight decreases from approximately 1000 g after delivery to about:',o:['50 g','200 g','100 g','500 g'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine weight falls from approximately 1 kg (1000 g) immediately after delivery to about 100 g by the end of the puerperium, a tenfold reduction achieved by autolysis of myometrial cells.<br><br>Each cell shrinks as enzymatic digestion of cytoplasm reduces its size; cell number is essentially preserved. Released protein is excreted in the urine. Breastfeeding accelerates the process via oxytocin-driven uterine contraction.<br><br>A (50 g) is below the typical non-pregnant weight. B (200 g) is heavier than typical end-puerperium. D (500 g) is half the immediate post-delivery weight.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The first postpartum ovulation in non-lactating women usually occurs around:',o:['6 weeks','4 weeks','2 weeks','12 weeks'],a:0,
    e:`In non-lactating women, the first postpartum ovulation usually occurs around 6 weeks after delivery, sometimes as early as 4 weeks. Without prolactin\'s suppression of GnRH, the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis recovers quickly.<br><br>Contraception should be considered before the 6-week postnatal visit. The progestogen-only pill is generally safe in breastfeeding; oestrogen-containing methods are usually avoided in the first 6 weeks because of thromboembolism risk.<br><br>B (4 weeks) can occur but is not typical. C (2 weeks) is too early for most women. D (12 weeks) is far beyond typical resumption.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Lochia serosa mainly contains:',o:['Fresh blood and clots','Serous fluid and leukocytes','Leukocytes and mucus','Pure mucus'],a:1,
    e:`Lochia serosa is the second phase of lochia (days 4 to 10) and contains mainly serous fluid and leukocytes, with small amounts of cervical mucus and minimal residual blood from the regenerating endometrium.<br><br>It follows lochia rubra (red, days 1 to 3, mainly blood and decidual debris) and precedes lochia alba (yellow-white, after day 10, mainly leukocytes and mucus). The progression mirrors endometrial regeneration from the basal layer.<br><br>A (fresh blood and clots) is lochia rubra. C (leukocytes and mucus) is closer to lochia alba. D (pure mucus) is not a normal lochial composition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological change occurs in the cardiovascular system during early puerperium?',o:['Decreased cardiac output','Increased blood volume','Mobilization of extravascular fluid','Decreased stroke volume'],a:2,
    e:`In early puerperium, the cardiovascular system mobilises extravascular fluid accumulated during pregnancy back into the circulation. Pregnancy adds about 6 to 8 litres of total body water, much of which is extracellular.<br><br>This mobilisation is excreted as increased diuresis and diaphoresis during the first postpartum week, producing early weight loss. Cardiac output remains elevated for several days before gradually returning to non-pregnant levels.<br><br>A (decreased cardiac output) occurs only later. B (raised blood volume) is opposite to mobilisation. D (decreased stroke volume) occurs only later.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman notices milk secretion from breasts triggered by infant crying. This is due to release of:',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Cortisol'],a:1,
    e:`Milk secretion triggered by infant crying or other auditory or visual cues is the let-down (milk-ejection) reflex, mediated by oxytocin from the maternal posterior pituitary contracting myoepithelial cells around alveoli and ducts.<br><br>Although suckling is the primary stimulus, the reflex can be conditioned to non-tactile cues. Stress inhibits the reflex and is a common cause of perceived inadequate milk supply in early breastfeeding mothers.<br><br>A (oestrogen) is not the let-down hormone. C (prolactin) drives synthesis, not ejection. D (cortisol) supports lactation but does not trigger let-down.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The external cervical os typically closes by approximately:',o:['End of second week','End of first week','End of third week','End of sixth week'],a:0,
    e:`The internal cervical os usually closes by the end of the second week postpartum. In the first few days the cervix admits two fingers; by the end of the first week, only one finger.<br><br>The external os, by contrast, usually remains permanently open in a parous slit-shape, distinguishing it from the circular nulliparous os. Persistent open internal os beyond 2 weeks suggests retained products of conception.<br><br>B (end of first week) is too early for full closure. C (end of third week) is later than typical. D (end of sixth week) is when overall involution is complete.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The process of breakdown of enlarged uterine muscle cells after delivery is known as:',o:['Hypertrophy','Hyperplasia','Metaplasia','Autolysis'],a:3,
    e:`Autolysis is the process by which the enlarged myometrial cells of the pregnant uterus break down their own cytoplasm through enzymatic digestion. The cells shrink in size while cell number is largely preserved.<br><br>Released protein is absorbed into the bloodstream and excreted in the urine. Autolysis is the main mechanism of uterine involution, reducing uterine weight from approximately 1000 g at delivery to about 100 g by the end of puerperium.<br><br>A (hypertrophy) is cell enlargement. B (hyperplasia) is increase in cell number. C (metaplasia) is change in cell type.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, pelvic floor muscles gradually regain tone. Which exercise is commonly recommended to strengthen them?',o:['Kegel exercises','Valsalva maneuver','Abdominal crunches','Squatting'],a:0,
    e:`Kegel exercises (pelvic floor muscle exercises) are the standard recommendation to strengthen pelvic floor muscles postpartum. They aim to improve tone of the levator ani and reduce risks of urinary incontinence and prolapse.<br><br>Although large randomised trials have not conclusively shown prevention of incontinence or prolapse, the exercises are unlikely to be harmful and improve pelvic floor awareness, helping women recognise and report dysfunction earlier.<br><br>B (Valsalva manoeuvre) raises pelvic floor pressure rather than strengthening. C (abdominal crunches) targets abdominal muscles. D (squatting) is not specifically pelvic floor.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The decidua remaining after delivery is gradually shed in the form of:',o:['Placental fragments','Lochial discharge','Cervical mucus','Endometrial polyps'],a:1,
    e:`The decidua remaining after delivery is shed in the form of lochial discharge. Only the superficial layer of decidua becomes necrotic and is sloughed; the basal layer regenerates new endometrium and is retained.<br><br>Lochia progresses from rubra (red, blood and decidual debris) to serosa (pink-brown, serous fluid and leukocytes) to alba (yellow-white, leukocytes and mucus) over about 4 to 6 weeks.<br><br>A (placental fragments) shed in lochia would be abnormal. C (cervical mucus) is unrelated. D (endometrial polyps) are pathological growths.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone inhibits ovulation during lactation?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:3,
    e:`Prolactin inhibits ovulation during lactation by suppressing GnRH pulsatility from the hypothalamus, which in turn reduces pituitary FSH and LH and prevents follicular development.<br><br>Suckling triggers prolactin release; the more frequent and prolonged the suckling, the more profound the suppression. Lactational amenorrhoea is reliable contraception only with exclusive breastfeeding in the first 6 months.<br><br>A (oestrogen) and B (progesterone) are low in lactation. C (oxytocin) drives milk ejection but does not inhibit GnRH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The typical duration of lochia rubra is approximately:',o:['10-14 days','4-10 days','1-3 days','3 weeks'],a:2,
    e:`Lochia rubra typically lasts about 1 to 3 days postpartum. It is composed mainly of blood and necrotic decidual debris from the superficial decidua sloughed after placental separation.<br><br>It transitions to lochia serosa (pink-brown, days 4 to 10) and then to lochia alba (yellow-white, from about day 10 for up to a month). Persistent rubra suggests delayed involution from infection or retained tissue.<br><br>A (10 to 14 days) extends into the alba phase. B (4 to 10 days) is the serosa range. D (3 weeks) is far beyond rubra duration.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman complains of afterpains while breastfeeding. These are caused by:',o:['Estrogen release','Oxytocin-induced uterine contractions','Progesterone withdrawal','Prolactin deficiency'],a:1,
    e:`After-pains during breastfeeding are caused by oxytocin-induced uterine contractions. Suckling triggers oxytocin release from the posterior pituitary, contracting both the breast myoepithelium for milk ejection and the uterine myometrium.<br><br>After-pains are more pronounced in multiparous women whose myometrium is more responsive to oxytocin. They may require simple analgesia. The contractions accelerate uterine involution, contributing to a smaller uterus in breastfeeding mothers.<br><br>A (oestrogen release) is not the cause. C (progesterone withdrawal) occurred at delivery. D (prolactin deficiency) does not cause cramps.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The most important mechanism preventing postpartum hemorrhage during puerperium is:',o:['Uterine retraction','Cervical contraction','Vaginal muscle tone','Platelet activation'],a:0,
    e:`Uterine retraction is the main mechanism preventing postpartum haemorrhage. Sustained shortening of the lattice-arranged myometrial fibres compresses the spiral arteries running through the uterine wall, occluding placental bed bleeding.<br><br>This living-ligature effect is far more important than coagulation in initial haemostasis. Failure of retraction (uterine atony) is the leading cause of PPH and is treated with massage, uterotonics, and if needed surgical intervention.<br><br>B (cervical contraction) does not control placental bed bleeding. C (vaginal muscle tone) is unrelated. D (platelet activation) is secondary to muscle compression.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, which metabolic change commonly occurs?',o:['Increased insulin resistance','Decreased metabolism','Increased diuresis','Reduced renal filtration'],a:2,
    e:`Increased diuresis is a common metabolic change of early puerperium. The increased fluid load of pregnancy is mobilised from the extracellular space and excreted in the first postpartum week through diuresis and diaphoresis.<br><br>Pregnancy adds approximately 6 to 8 litres of total body water. Diuresis contributes to early postpartum weight loss. Insulin resistance from pregnancy resolves rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>A (raised insulin resistance) actually falls. B (decreased metabolism) is incorrect. D (reduced renal filtration) is the opposite of what occurs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman develops breast engorgement on day 3. Which physiological event causes this?',o:['Increase in progesterone','Decreased blood supply','Reduced prolactin','Increased milk secretion and vascular congestion'],a:3,
    e:`Breast engorgement on day 3 postpartum is caused by the combination of increased milk secretion (lactogenesis stage II) and vascular and lymphatic congestion of the breast tissue as the milk supply establishes.<br><br>Lactogenesis II is triggered by the fall in placental progesterone and oestrogen, which removes their inhibition of prolactin\'s action on the alveolar cells. Engorgement usually settles with frequent feeding and proper latching.<br><br>A (raised progesterone) is opposite of postpartum physiology. B (decreased blood supply) is incorrect. C (reduced prolactin) opposes lactation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine cavity becomes lined with new endometrium usually by:',o:['5 days','10 days','3 weeks','6 weeks'],a:2,
    e:`The uterine cavity is fully relined with new endometrium by approximately the third week postpartum. Regeneration occurs from the basal layer of the endometrium, the layer adjacent to the myometrium, which was not shed at delivery.<br><br>Only the superficial decidua is sloughed as lochia. The placental implantation site itself takes longer, healing completely by about 6 weeks. Persistent rubra beyond the regeneration window suggests infection or retained tissue.<br><br>A (5 days) is too early. B (10 days) is still during lochia serosa. D (6 weeks) is full puerperium completion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological change contributes to constipation in early puerperium?',o:['Increased intestinal motility','Decreased progesterone levels','Increased estrogen levels','Reduced abdominal tone and pain'],a:3,
    e:`Constipation in early puerperium is contributed to by reduced abdominal tone from stretched abdominal muscles and pain from perineal trauma, sutured episiotomy, prolapsed haemorrhoids or anal fissures.<br><br>Other contributors include intrapartum dehydration, dietary disruption and opiate analgesia. Adequate fluid and fibre intake usually suffice. Avoidance of straining is critical after third or fourth-degree tears, with stool softeners often prescribed.<br><br>A (raised motility) is the opposite. B (decreased progesterone) would actually relieve constipation. C (raised oestrogen) is not the cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The fallopian tubes return to their nonpregnant size approximately by:',o:['1 week','2 weeks','6 weeks','3 months'],a:1,
    e:`The fallopian tubes return to their non-pregnant size by approximately 2 weeks postpartum, paralleling the early stages of uterine involution. The tubes had elongated and become more vascular during pregnancy.<br><br>Other genital tract structures show different timelines: the uterus becomes a pelvic organ again by 2 weeks, complete uterine involution takes 6 weeks, and the placental implantation site heals by 6 weeks.<br><br>A (1 week) is too early. C (6 weeks) is when overall involution is complete. D (3 months) is far beyond.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During lactation, which hormone primarily stimulates milk synthesis?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:0,
    e:`Prolactin from the anterior pituitary is the principal hormone stimulating milk synthesis during lactation. Its action on alveolar secretory cells produces milk proteins; levels rise up to 20-fold during pregnancy and lactation.<br><br>Suckling stimulates prolactin release by reducing hypothalamic dopamine (prolactin-inhibiting factor). Bromocryptine, a dopamine agonist, suppresses prolactin and can be used to arrest unwanted lactation.<br><br>B (oxytocin) drives milk ejection, not synthesis. C (oestrogen) inhibits prolactin\'s action. D (progesterone) inhibits lactation antenatally.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The physiological reason for postpartum bradycardia in some women is:',o:['Reduced blood volume','Placental hormone release','Decreased cardiac output','Increased vagal tone'],a:3,
    e:`Postpartum bradycardia in some women results from increased vagal tone in response to the rapid haemodynamic changes after delivery. Mobilisation of extravascular fluid raises preload and triggers compensatory vagal slowing.<br><br>It is usually transient, lasting up to a week, and well tolerated. Marked or symptomatic bradycardia warrants further evaluation, particularly when associated with pre-existing cardiac disease or postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>A (reduced blood volume) actually causes tachycardia. B (placental hormone release) does not cause bradycardia. C (decreased cardiac output) is opposite of postpartum physiology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological change in breasts occurs during early puerperium?',o:['Decreased vascularity','Increased glandular activity','Reduced ductal growth','Fat replacement'],a:1,
    e:`In early puerperium the breasts show increased glandular activity. Falling placental progesterone and oestrogen remove inhibition of prolactin\'s action on alveolar cells, triggering lactogenesis stage II by 48 to 72 hours.<br><br>Vascular and lymphatic congestion accompanies the increased glandular activity, contributing to breast engorgement around day 3. Established suckling regulates ongoing milk supply through repeated prolactin release.<br><br>A (decreased vascularity) is opposite. C (reduced ductal growth) is incorrect. D (fat replacement) is the post-weaning change, not early puerperium.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common time for onset of lactogenesis stage II (copious milk secretion) is:',o:['Within 12 hours postpartum','24 hours postpartum','48-72 hours postpartum','After one week'],a:2,
    e:`Lactogenesis stage II, the onset of copious milk secretion, typically occurs 48 to 72 hours postpartum. It is triggered by the sharp fall in placental progesterone and oestrogen after placental delivery.<br><br>Stage I (secretory differentiation) occurs antenatally with colostrum production from mid-pregnancy. Stage II depends on the postpartum hormonal change. Delayed onset (beyond 72 hours) is associated with retained placenta, severe stress or diabetes.<br><br>A (within 12 hours) is too early. B (24 hours) is too early. D (after one week) is delayed.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the uterine arteries undergo which physiological change?',o:['Progressive narrowing and obliteration','Immediate disappearance','Complete thrombosis and fibrosis','Increased dilation'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine arteries undergo progressive narrowing and obliteration during the puerperium. Vasoconstriction, intimal proliferation and gradual fibrous obliteration reduce blood supply to the uterus as it involutes.<br><br>These changes accompany regression of the placental implantation site, which is fully healed by approximately 6 weeks. The reduced vascularity is part of the overall return of the uterus to its non-pregnant state.<br><br>B (immediate disappearance) is incorrect. C (complete thrombosis and fibrosis) is too extreme. D (raised dilation) is the opposite.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'A postpartum woman experiences night sweats during the first week after delivery. This occurs due to:',o:['Estrogen surge','Increased prolactin','Fluid mobilization and hormonal changes','Placental hormone secretion'],a:2,
    e:`Postpartum night sweats during the first week reflect mobilisation of the extravascular fluid accumulated during pregnancy and the rapid hormonal changes (especially falling oestrogen) that follow placental delivery.<br><br>Pregnancy adds approximately 6 to 8 litres of total body water. The combination of hypothalamic adjustment to lower oestrogen and fluid offload via diaphoresis and diuresis produces this temporary symptom.<br><br>A (oestrogen surge) is opposite of postpartum physiology. B (raised prolactin) does not cause sweats. D (placental hormone secretion) ceases at delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological factor primarily delays ovulation during exclusive breastfeeding?',o:['Elevated estrogen','Reduced oxytocin','Increased progesterone','High prolactin levels suppressing GnRH'],a:3,
    e:`Ovulation during exclusive breastfeeding is delayed mainly by high prolactin levels suppressing GnRH pulsatility from the hypothalamus, which reduces pituitary FSH and LH and prevents follicular development.<br><br>The lactational amenorrhoea method relies on this physiology and is a reliable contraceptive only with exclusive breastfeeding (including night feeds), amenorrhoea, and within the first 6 months postpartum.<br><br>A (raised oestrogen) is opposite. B (reduced oxytocin) is incorrect; oxytocin rises with suckling. C (raised progesterone) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the uterus becomes a pelvic organ again approximately by:',o:['1 week','2 weeks','3 weeks','6 weeks'],a:1,
    e:`By approximately 2 weeks postpartum the uterus has involuted enough to become a pelvic organ again, no longer palpable abdominally above the symphysis pubis. The fundus descends by about 1 cm per day.<br><br>Complete involution to the non-pregnant size of about 100 g takes 6 weeks. Persistent abdominal palpability beyond 2 weeks suggests subinvolution from retained products of conception, infection, fibroids or a full bladder.<br><br>A (1 week) is too early. C (3 weeks) is later than typical. D (6 weeks) is full involution.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The average weight of the uterus immediately after delivery is approximately:',o:['1000 g','500 g','200 g','1500 g'],a:0,
    e:`Immediately after delivery the uterus weighs approximately 1000 g (1 kg). It involutes by autolysis to about 100 g by the end of the puerperium, a tenfold reduction over 6 weeks.<br><br>Autolysis is enzymatic digestion of cytoplasm that shrinks each cell while preserving cell number. Released protein is excreted in the urine. The fundus descends by about 1 cm per day from the level of the umbilicus.<br><br>B (500 g) is half the immediate post-delivery weight. C (200 g) is closer to mid-involution. D (1500 g) exceeds the typical post-delivery weight.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental implantation site is usually completely healed by:',o:['2 weeks','6 weeks','3 weeks','10 weeks'],a:1,
    e:`The placental implantation site is usually completely healed by approximately 6 weeks postpartum. Healing involves regeneration of the endometrium and progressive narrowing and obliteration of uterine vessels supplying the site.<br><br>Endometrial regeneration of the rest of the cavity is complete by about 3 weeks. The placental site takes longer because of the larger raw area exposed by separation. Healing is checked at the 6-week postnatal examination.<br><br>A (2 weeks) is too early. C (3 weeks) is when general endometrial regeneration is complete. D (10 weeks) is beyond standard healing.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological event occurs in the cervix during puerperium?',o:['Immediate closure','Increased glandular secretion','Permanent dilation','Gradual shortening and thickening'],a:3,
    e:`During puerperium the cervix gradually shortens and thickens, regaining tone over the first weeks. In early days it admits two fingers, by the end of week one a single finger, and the internal os closes by week two.<br><br>The external os usually remains permanently open in a parous slit-shape, distinguishing it from the circular nulliparous os. This characteristic is detected on speculum examination.<br><br>A (immediate closure) is incorrect; closure is gradual. B (raised glandular secretion) is not the typical change. C (permanent dilation) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The major physiological stimulus for continued prolactin secretion postpartum is:',o:['Increased estrogen','Maternal stress','Infant suckling','Placental hormones'],a:2,
    e:`Continued prolactin secretion postpartum is driven primarily by infant suckling. Nipple stimulation reduces release of dopamine (prolactin-inhibiting factor) from the hypothalamus, allowing prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary.<br><br>Prolactin peaks within 45 minutes of suckling and rises up to 20-fold during pregnancy and lactation. Suckling-driven prolactin maintains milk synthesis and suppresses GnRH, contributing to lactational amenorrhoea.<br><br>A (raised oestrogen) inhibits prolactin\'s effect. B (maternal stress) acutely raises prolactin but is not the major postpartum stimulus. D (placental hormones) cease at delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the pelvic ligaments gradually:',o:['Regain tone slowly','Shorten immediately','Undergo fibrosis','Become permanently lax'],a:0,
    e:`During puerperium the pelvic ligaments, softened by relaxin during pregnancy, gradually regain tone over the first weeks postpartum. The pubic symphysis and sacroiliac joints, in particular, return towards their non-pregnant configuration.<br><br>Persistent symphyseal separation occurs in around 1 in 800 vaginal deliveries and presents with symphyseal pain, a waddling gait and a palpable interpubic gap. Treatment is rest, anti-inflammatories, physiotherapy and a pelvic corset.<br><br>B (immediate shortening) is incorrect. C (fibrosis) is not the typical recovery. D (permanent laxity) is abnormal.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which metabolic change contributes to postpartum weight loss during the first week?',o:['Increased appetite','Reduced metabolism','Increased insulin resistance','Increased diuresis and diaphoresis'],a:3,
    e:`Postpartum weight loss in the first week is contributed to by increased diuresis and diaphoresis, which mobilise the 6 to 8 litres of extravascular fluid accumulated during pregnancy back into the circulation for excretion.<br><br>Together with delivery of the fetus, placenta and amniotic fluid, this can produce 5 to 7 kg of immediate weight loss, with further fluid offload over the first postpartum week. Lactation also raises caloric expenditure.<br><br>A (raised appetite) does not directly cause weight loss. B (reduced metabolism) opposes weight loss. C (raised insulin resistance) is opposite of postpartum physiology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The vaginal epithelium during early puerperium becomes:',o:['Thickened due to estrogen','Hyperplastic','Atrophic due to low estrogen','Keratinized'],a:2,
    e:`During early puerperium the vaginal epithelium becomes atrophic due to low circulating oestrogen. Placental oestrogen has fallen sharply at delivery, and in breastfeeding women high prolactin further suppresses ovarian oestrogen.<br><br>This may produce vaginal dryness, dyspareunia and contact bleeding, more pronounced in lactating women. Symptoms usually settle as ovarian function resumes, particularly after weaning. Topical oestrogen can be used if symptoms persist.<br><br>A (thickened due to oestrogen) is opposite. B (hyperplastic) is incorrect. D (keratinised) is not characteristic.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiological mechanism contributes to closure of uterine blood vessels after delivery?',o:['Platelet aggregation only','Myometrial contraction compressing vessels','Cervical closure','Vaginal contraction'],a:1,
    e:`Closure of uterine blood vessels after delivery is driven by myometrial contraction compressing vessels running through the uterine wall. Sustained contraction and retraction occlude the spiral arteries supplying the placental bed.<br><br>This living-ligature effect is the principal initial haemostatic mechanism, more important than coagulation. Failure (uterine atony) leaves vessels open and is the leading cause of PPH; oxytocin reinforces contraction clinically.<br><br>A (platelets only) is secondary to muscle compression. C (cervical closure) does not control placental bed bleeding. D (vaginal contraction) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, the uterine fundus is no longer palpable abdominally usually by:',o:['10 days','5 days','2 weeks','4 weeks'],a:0,
    e:`By approximately 10 days the uterine fundus is no longer reliably palpable abdominally as it descends behind the symphysis pubis. The fundus descends by about 1 cm per day from the level of the umbilicus.<br><br>By 2 weeks the uterus has become a pelvic organ again. Persistent abdominal palpability beyond 2 weeks suggests subinvolution from retained products of conception, infection or fibroids.<br><br>B (5 days) is too early; the fundus is still high. C (2 weeks) is when the uterus is fully a pelvic organ. D (4 weeks) is far later than abdominal disappearance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The main physiological cause of breast engorgement during puerperium is:',o:['Reduced milk production','Decreased prolactin','Increased milk production and vascular congestion','Reduced blood flow'],a:2,
    e:`Breast engorgement around day 3 postpartum is caused by the combination of increased milk production at lactogenesis II and concurrent vascular and lymphatic congestion of the breast tissue.<br><br>Lactogenesis II is triggered by the fall in placental progesterone and oestrogen after delivery. Engorgement usually settles with frequent feeding and good latching. Refractory or painful engorgement may require analgesia and warm or cold packs.<br><br>A (reduced milk production) opposes engorgement. B (decreased prolactin) opposes lactation. D (reduced blood flow) is opposite.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'During puerperium, ovulation in exclusively breastfeeding women is most commonly suppressed due to:',o:['High estrogen levels','Elevated prolactin inhibiting GnRH secretion','Increased progesterone','Increased oxytocin'],a:1,
    e:`Ovulation suppression in exclusively breastfeeding women is mediated mainly by elevated prolactin inhibiting GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus, which lowers pituitary FSH and LH and prevents follicular development.<br><br>Lactational amenorrhoea is reliable contraception only when breastfeeding is exclusive (including night feeds), the woman is amenorrhoeic, and within 6 months of delivery. Otherwise additional contraception is needed.<br><br>A (high oestrogen) is opposite of lactating physiology. C (raised progesterone) is not the suppressor. D (raised oxytocin) does not inhibit GnRH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: The puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Cardiotocography (CTG) primarily assesses:',o:['Maternal uterine anatomy','Placental blood flow','Amniotic fluid volume','Fetal heart rate and uterine contractions'],a:3,
    e:`Cardiotocography is a continuous tracing of the fetal heart rate combined with simultaneous recording of uterine activity, used to assess fetal wellbeing during labour and in selected antenatal situations.<br><br>Two external transducers are placed on the abdomen: a Doppler ultrasound for the fetal heart rate and a tocodynamometer for uterine contractions. Internal monitoring with a fetal scalp electrode is used when external recording is poor.<br><br>A (uterine anatomy) is assessed by ultrasound or examination. B (placental flow) is assessed by Doppler studies. C (amniotic fluid) is measured by ultrasound.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'The normal baseline fetal heart rate on CTG is:',o:['110-160 bpm','100-120 bpm','90-110 bpm','160-180 bpm'],a:0,
    e:`The normal baseline fetal heart rate at term is between 110 and 160 beats per minute, averaged over a 20-minute interval or longer. Higher rates are tachycardia and lower rates bradycardia.<br><br>Baseline rate falls with advancing gestation as parasympathetic tone matures; pre-term, 160 bpm is the upper limit of normal. The baseline is best determined over 5 to 10 minutes excluding accelerations and decelerations.<br><br>B (100 to 120) is too low. C (90 to 110) is bradycardic. D (160 to 180) is tachycardic.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Baseline fetal tachycardia is defined as fetal heart rate greater than:',o:['140 bpm','150 bpm','180 bpm','160 bpm'],a:3,
    e:`Baseline fetal tachycardia is defined as a sustained fetal heart rate greater than 160 beats per minute. Causes include maternal or fetal infection, acute fetal hypoxia, fetal anaemia, maternal pyrexia and certain drugs such as ritodrine.<br><br>Mild tachycardia (160 to 180 bpm) is a non-reassuring feature; sustained rate above 180 bpm is abnormal. Persistent tachycardia, particularly with reduced variability or decelerations, raises concern for fetal compromise.<br><br>A (140 bpm) and B (150 bpm) are within normal range. C (180 bpm) is the threshold for severe tachycardia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Baseline fetal bradycardia is defined as fetal heart rate less than:',o:['120 bpm','100 bpm','110 bpm','90 bpm'],a:2,
    e:`Baseline fetal bradycardia is defined as a sustained fetal heart rate less than 110 beats per minute. Causes include cord compression, congenital heart block, severe hypoxia and maternal hypothermia or beta-blocker use.<br><br>Mild bradycardia (100 to 109 bpm) for short periods may not be sinister, but persistent or deepening bradycardia warrants urgent assessment. Sustained rate below 100 bpm is abnormal and may prompt expedited delivery.<br><br>A (120 bpm) is within normal range. B (100 bpm) is more severe bradycardia. D (90 bpm) is severe bradycardia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Baseline variability in CTG represents:',o:['Fluctuations in fetal heart rate baseline','Uterine contraction intensity','Maternal heart rate changes','Fetal breathing movements'],a:0,
    e:`Baseline variability represents the longer-term fluctuations in baseline fetal heart rate, occurring 2 to 6 times per minute, reflecting the integrity of the fetal autonomic nervous system.<br><br>Normal variability is 5 to 25 bpm and indicates a non-hypoxic fetus with mature autonomic control. Variability is reduced by hypoxia, fetal sleep, infection, opioids and hypnotics. Sleep cycles last 20 to 30 minutes.<br><br>B (uterine contractions) are recorded by the tocodynamometer. C (maternal heart rate) is not the focus. D (fetal breathing) is part of the biophysical profile.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Normal baseline variability on CTG is:',o:['1-5 bpm','5-25 bpm','30-40 bpm','>40 bpm'],a:1,
    e:`Normal baseline variability on CTG is between 5 and 25 bpm, reflecting an intact fetal autonomic nervous system. Variability less than 5 bpm for more than 40 minutes is non-reassuring; less than 5 bpm beyond 90 minutes is abnormal.<br><br>Fetal sleep cycles can normally produce reduced variability for 20 to 30 minutes, after which a period of normal variability should follow. Persistent reduction beyond sleep cycles raises concern for hypoxia.<br><br>A (1 to 5 bpm) is reduced variability. C (30 to 40 bpm) is excessive. D (above 40 bpm) is uncommon and abnormal.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Reduced baseline variability may indicate:',o:['Fetal sleep','Fetal hypoxia','All of the above','Maternal sedation'],a:2,
    e:`Reduced baseline variability may indicate fetal sleep, fetal hypoxia, maternal sedation, prematurity, fetal infection, or drug effects (opioids, magnesium sulphate, hypnotics). All listed possibilities apply.<br><br>Sleep cycles produce normal reduction lasting 20 to 30 minutes. Persistent reduction beyond a sleep cycle, especially with other non-reassuring features, warrants further assessment with fetal scalp blood sampling or expedited delivery.<br><br>A (fetal sleep) and B (fetal hypoxia) and D (maternal sedation) are individually correct. The combined option captures the full clinical reality.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Accelerations in CTG are defined as:',o:['Decreases in fetal heart rate','Temporary increases in fetal heart rate','Absence of variability','Persistent tachycardia'],a:1,
    e:`Accelerations on CTG are temporary increases in fetal heart rate of at least 15 bpm above baseline, lasting at least 15 seconds. Two or more accelerations in 20 to 30 minutes define a reactive trace.<br><br>Accelerations are a positive sign of fetal health and an intact fetal autonomic nervous system. Their absence in labour is of uncertain significance, but their presence is reassuring at any time.<br><br>A (decreases) describes decelerations. C (absence of variability) is a separate feature. D (persistent tachycardia) is a baseline change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'The presence of accelerations on CTG usually indicates:',o:['Fetal well-being','Fetal distress','Placental insufficiency','Cord compression'],a:0,
    e:`Accelerations on CTG indicate fetal wellbeing. Their presence reflects an intact fetal autonomic nervous system and the absence of significant fetal hypoxia.<br><br>Two or more accelerations in 20 to 30 minutes define a reactive trace. The presence of accelerations is reassuring whether antepartum or intrapartum, although their absence in labour is of uncertain significance.<br><br>B (fetal distress) is associated with decelerations and reduced variability. C (placental insufficiency) is suggested by late decelerations. D (cord compression) produces variable decelerations.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Early decelerations in CTG are most commonly caused by:',o:['Placental insufficiency','Umbilical cord compression','Uterine rupture','Fetal head compression'],a:3,
    e:`Early decelerations are caused by fetal head compression. They begin and end with the contraction, mirror its shape, and represent a vagally mediated reflex from the head being compressed during descent.<br><br>Early decelerations are usually a normal feature of advanced labour and not a sign of fetal compromise. They are physiological in origin and do not indicate hypoxia.<br><br>A (placental insufficiency) causes late decelerations. B (cord compression) causes variable decelerations. C (uterine rupture) produces prolonged or sudden bradycardia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Variable decelerations are most commonly associated with:',o:['Maternal hypertension','Cord compression','Placental abruption','Fetal anemia'],a:1,
    e:`Variable decelerations are most commonly associated with umbilical cord compression. They vary in shape, depth and timing relative to contractions, reflecting the irregular pattern of cord occlusion.<br><br>Cord compression briefly raises fetal blood pressure, triggering a baroreceptor-mediated drop in heart rate. Most variable decelerations are not sinister; deeper, longer or atypical variables (loss of shoulders) raise concern.<br><br>A (maternal hypertension) is not the typical cause. C (placental abruption) typically produces prolonged decelerations. D (fetal anaemia) produces sinusoidal patterns.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Late decelerations are typically associated with:',o:['Placental insufficiency','Cord compression','Fetal movement','Head compression'],a:0,
    e:`Late decelerations are typically associated with placental insufficiency. They begin after the contraction starts and recover after the contraction ends, reflecting hypoxic stress as fetal oxygen reserves are exhausted during contractions.<br><br>Late decelerations represent inadequate placental perfusion or oxygen transfer. They are particularly worrying when recurrent or accompanied by reduced variability or absent accelerations, suggesting evolving fetal hypoxia and acidosis.<br><br>B (cord compression) produces variable decelerations. C (fetal movement) produces accelerations. D (head compression) produces early decelerations.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Recurrent late decelerations on CTG suggest:',o:['Normal fetal response','Uterine rupture','Fetal hypoxia','Fetal arrhythmia'],a:2,
    e:`Recurrent late decelerations on CTG strongly suggest fetal hypoxia. They reflect placental insufficiency: fetal oxygen reserves are exhausted during each contraction, producing a vagally and chemoreceptor-mediated drop in heart rate.<br><br>Combined with reduced variability or absent accelerations, recurrent late decelerations warrant further assessment with fetal scalp blood sampling or expedited delivery, particularly if any reversible causes have been addressed.<br><br>A (normal response) is incorrect; lates are pathological. B (uterine rupture) typically gives prolonged bradycardia. D (arrhythmia) shows different baseline patterns.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'A sinusoidal pattern on CTG is most strongly associated with:',o:['Fetal sleep cycle','Maternal hypotension','Placental abruption','Fetal anemia'],a:3,
    e:`A sinusoidal CTG pattern, with smooth wave-like oscillations of the fetal heart rate, is most strongly associated with severe fetal anaemia, including from rhesus isoimmunisation, fetomaternal haemorrhage or parvovirus B19 infection.<br><br>The pattern is regular and persistent, lasting at least 10 minutes, with reduced or absent variability. It is an ominous finding warranting urgent assessment, often with fetal middle cerebral artery Doppler and consideration of intrauterine transfusion or delivery.<br><br>A (fetal sleep cycle) shows pseudo-sinusoidal but variable patterns. B (maternal hypotension) does not produce this pattern. C (placental abruption) produces prolonged decelerations.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Which investigation is commonly used along with CTG to assess fetal well-being?',o:['Chest X-ray','CT scan','Biophysical profile','Liver function test'],a:2,
    e:`The biophysical profile (BPP) is commonly used along with CTG to assess fetal wellbeing. It combines CTG with ultrasound assessment of fetal breathing movements, gross body movements, fetal tone and amniotic fluid volume.<br><br>Each of the five variables scores 0 or 2, giving a total of 0 to 10. A score of 8 or 10 is normal; 6 is equivocal and repeated; 4 or below is abnormal and may warrant delivery. Doppler studies of umbilical and fetal vessels are also used.<br><br>A (chest X-ray) is not used. B (CT scan) is rarely used in obstetrics. D (LFTs) is unrelated to fetal wellbeing.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'A reactive CTG trace typically shows:',o:['No accelerations','Two or more accelerations within 20 minutes','Persistent tachycardia','Absent variability'],a:1,
    e:`A reactive CTG trace shows two or more accelerations in 20 minutes, with normal baseline rate and variability and no decelerations. Reactivity reflects an intact fetal autonomic nervous system and is reassuring of fetal wellbeing.<br><br>Non-reactive traces require further assessment with extended monitoring, biophysical profile or umbilical artery Doppler. The absence of accelerations in labour is of uncertain significance.<br><br>A (no accelerations) is non-reactive. C (persistent tachycardia) is a baseline abnormality. D (absent variability) is a separate non-reassuring feature.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Non-reactive CTG suggests:',o:['Normal fetal status','Maternal infection','Fetal macrosomia','Possible fetal compromise'],a:3,
    e:`A non-reactive CTG suggests possible fetal compromise. The absence of accelerations and other reassuring features may indicate hypoxia, although fetal sleep cycles and certain medications can also produce non-reactive traces.<br><br>Further assessment is needed: extended monitoring, biophysical profile, fetal scalp blood sampling, or umbilical artery Doppler. Persistent non-reactivity with other non-reassuring features may prompt expedited delivery.<br><br>A (normal status) does not produce non-reactivity. B (maternal infection) is not the typical cause. C (fetal macrosomia) is not associated with non-reactivity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Which parameter is NOT part of CTG interpretation?',o:['Amniotic fluid index','Variability','Accelerations','Baseline heart rate'],a:0,
    e:`Amniotic fluid index is not part of CTG interpretation. CTG assesses four features: baseline fetal heart rate, baseline variability, accelerations and decelerations, with simultaneous recording of uterine contractions.<br><br>Amniotic fluid volume is a separate ultrasound parameter and one of the variables in the biophysical profile. CTG features are individually classified as reassuring, non-reassuring or abnormal to give an overall normal, suspicious or pathological trace.<br><br>B (variability), C (accelerations) and D (baseline rate) are all part of CTG interpretation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'CTG monitoring is most useful in:',o:['Normal pregnancies only','High-risk pregnancies','Postnatal period','Neonatal care'],a:1,
    e:`Continuous CTG monitoring is most useful in high-risk pregnancies and labours, where the risk of fetal compromise is increased and ongoing assessment is needed to detect hypoxia early.<br><br>In low-risk labour, intermittent auscultation is recommended; routine continuous CTG raises caesarean and instrumental delivery rates without clear benefit. Indications for continuous CTG include meconium, abnormal auscultation, pyrexia, bleeding and oxytocin use.<br><br>A (normal pregnancies only) reverses the indication. C (postnatal period) is not relevant. D (neonatal care) uses different monitoring.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common cause of variable decelerations during labor is:',o:['Umbilical cord compression','Placental insufficiency','Maternal fever','Fetal anemia'],a:0,
    e:`Variable decelerations during labour are most commonly caused by umbilical cord compression. They vary in shape, depth and timing relative to contractions, reflecting the irregular pattern of cord occlusion.<br><br>Brief cord compression raises fetal blood pressure and triggers a baroreceptor-mediated drop in heart rate. Most variable decelerations are not sinister, but atypical variables (deep, prolonged, with loss of shoulders) raise concern for evolving hypoxia.<br><br>B (placental insufficiency) causes late decelerations. C (maternal fever) raises baseline rate. D (fetal anaemia) causes sinusoidal patterns.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Persistent fetal tachycardia on CTG may be caused by:',o:['Maternal fever','Fetal infection','Maternal dehydration','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`Persistent fetal tachycardia on CTG can be caused by maternal fever, fetal infection, maternal dehydration, acute fetal hypoxia, fetal anaemia and certain drugs such as ritodrine. All listed options apply.<br><br>Maternal pyrexia is the most common reversible cause and warrants treatment. Persistent tachycardia with reduced variability or decelerations, however, raises concern for fetal compromise and warrants further assessment.<br><br>A (maternal fever), B (fetal infection) and C (maternal dehydration) are individually correct, hence the combined option.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'CTG monitoring during labor primarily aims to detect:',o:['Maternal hypertension','Maternal anemia','Fetal hypoxia','Placental position'],a:2,
    e:`CTG monitoring during labour aims primarily to detect fetal hypoxia and acidosis early, allowing timely intervention to prevent neuronal damage and intrapartum fetal death.<br><br>Hypoxia produces characteristic changes: reduced variability, late decelerations, atypical variables, and tachycardia or bradycardia. The CTG has a high false-positive rate, so suspicious traces are often confirmed with fetal scalp blood sampling.<br><br>A (maternal hypertension) is monitored separately. B (maternal anaemia) is not assessed by CTG. D (placental position) is assessed by ultrasound.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Which feature indicates a reassuring CTG trace?',o:['Absent variability','Late decelerations','Sinusoidal pattern','Moderate variability'],a:3,
    e:`Moderate (normal) baseline variability of 5 to 25 bpm is a reassuring CTG feature, indicating an intact fetal autonomic nervous system and the absence of significant hypoxia.<br><br>A reassuring trace overall has a normal baseline (110 to 160 bpm), normal variability, accelerations and no decelerations. If all features are reassuring, the CTG is classified as normal under standard NICE criteria.<br><br>A (absent variability) is abnormal. B (late decelerations) is non-reassuring or abnormal. C (sinusoidal pattern) is abnormal.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'A prolonged deceleration in CTG is defined as a drop in fetal heart rate lasting:',o:['Less than 30 seconds','Less than 1 minute','More than 2 minutes','More than 10 minutes'],a:2,
    e:`A prolonged deceleration is defined as a drop in fetal heart rate lasting more than 2 minutes (some criteria use 3 minutes). Decelerations beyond 10 minutes are usually treated as a baseline change.<br><br>Causes include cord prolapse, uterine hyperstimulation, maternal hypotension after epidural, placental abruption and uterine rupture. Prolonged decelerations require immediate assessment and often expedited delivery if not rapidly resolved.<br><br>A (less than 30 seconds) is too brief. B (less than 1 minute) is also too brief. D (more than 10 minutes) is usually a baseline change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Continuous CTG monitoring is recommended in:',o:['High-risk labor','Low-risk labor','Postpartum period','Neonatal care'],a:0,
    e:`Continuous CTG monitoring is recommended in high-risk labour, where the risk of fetal compromise is increased. Routine continuous CTG in low-risk labour raises operative delivery rates without improving outcomes.<br><br>Indications include significant meconium-stained fluid, abnormal intermittent auscultation, maternal pyrexia, fresh vaginal bleeding, oxytocin augmentation and maternal request. Hepatitis C and HIV may contraindicate scalp electrodes.<br><br>B (low-risk labour) uses intermittent auscultation. C (postpartum period) does not need CTG. D (neonatal care) uses neonatal monitoring.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'A CTG showing recurrent late decelerations with reduced variability suggests:',o:['Normal labor pattern','Fetal hypoxia and acidosis','Fetal sleep cycle','Maternal dehydration'],a:1,
    e:`Recurrent late decelerations with reduced variability strongly suggest evolving fetal hypoxia and acidosis. The combination indicates inadequate placental oxygen transfer with exhausted fetal reserves and a compromised autonomic response.<br><br>Reversible causes (dehydration, hypotension, hyperstimulation) must be addressed; if the pattern persists, fetal scalp blood sampling or expedited delivery is needed. Persistent abnormal CTG without intervention risks neuronal damage and intrapartum fetal death.<br><br>A (normal pattern) is incorrect; this is pathological. C (sleep cycle) does not produce late decelerations. D (dehydration) may contribute but is not the diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'The sinusoidal CTG pattern is characterized by:',o:['Irregular baseline variability','Random accelerations','Rapid tachycardia','Smooth wave-like oscillations of fetal heart rate'],a:3,
    e:`The sinusoidal CTG pattern is characterised by smooth, regular wave-like oscillations of the fetal heart rate, with reduced or absent baseline variability and frequency of about 3 to 5 cycles per minute, lasting at least 10 minutes.<br><br>It is most strongly associated with severe fetal anaemia (rhesus isoimmunisation, fetomaternal haemorrhage, parvovirus B19) and is an ominous finding. Pseudo-sinusoidal patterns from fetal sucking are intermittent and less regular.<br><br>A (irregular variability) is not sinusoidal. B (random accelerations) is reactivity. C (rapid tachycardia) is a baseline change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'CTG trace showing normal baseline, normal variability, and accelerations without decelerations is classified as:',o:['Normal','Suspicious','Pathological','Abnormal'],a:0,
    e:`A CTG with normal baseline rate (110 to 160 bpm), normal variability (5 to 25 bpm), accelerations and no decelerations is classified as normal under standard NICE criteria.<br><br>If one feature is non-reassuring (others reassuring), the trace is suspicious. If two or more features are non-reassuring, or any single feature is abnormal, the trace is pathological. Pathological traces require further assessment or delivery.<br><br>B (suspicious) requires one non-reassuring feature. C (pathological) requires two non-reassuring or one abnormal feature. D (abnormal) overlaps with pathological.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Assessment of fetal wellbeing)</em>`},
    {q:'Which intervention is most appropriate when CTG shows persistent late decelerations?',o:['Ignore CTG findings','Continue routine monitoring only','Immediate delivery if unresolved','Delay labor'],a:2,
    e:`Persistent late decelerations indicate evolving fetal hypoxia from placental insufficiency. If reversible causes have been addressed and the pattern persists, immediate delivery is the most appropriate intervention to prevent severe acidosis and neuronal damage.<br><br>Reversible causes that should be checked first include dehydration, maternal hypotension after epidural, oxytocin-induced hyperstimulation and supine positioning. Fetal scalp blood sampling can clarify status if delivery is not immediately needed.<br><br>A (ignore CTG) is dangerous. B (continue routine monitoring) is inadequate for persistent lates. D (delay labour) does not address fetal compromise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`},
    {q:'Fetal scalp blood sampling during labor is used to assess:',o:['Maternal oxygenation','Fetal acid-base status','Amniotic fluid composition','Placental hormones'],a:1,
    e:`Fetal scalp blood sampling during labour assesses fetal acid-base status by measuring pH and base excess directly. It is used when the CTG is suspicious or pathological but delivery is not immediately mandated.<br><br>A pH of 7.25 or above is reassuring; 7.21 to 7.24 is borderline (repeat in 30 minutes); below 7.20 is abnormal and warrants immediate delivery. FBS reduces operative delivery rates by clarifying CTG findings and avoiding intervention for false-positive traces.<br><br>A (maternal oxygenation) is assessed differently. C (amniotic fluid composition) is not the purpose. D (placental hormones) are not measured during labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Labour: normal and abnormal)</em>`}
  ];
})();